{ Hello chess friends and welcome to this course! We are GM Yaro Zherebukh and FM Dalton Perrine, both based in Chicago, and we will be your guides on your journey of learning how to play 1. Nf3 with the emphasis on 2. b3 in the majority of the lines.   This course is intended for chess players of all levels, who would like to memorize far less theory than in the other major starting moves @@StartBracket@@1. e4, 1. d4, 1. c4@@EndBracket@@, but yet still be able to put their opponents to the real test and fight for the advantage.   You can make 1. Nf3 your main repertoire or use it as a surprise weapon - in either case, learning new openings, pawn structures, and plans will enrich your chess knowledge and make your chess toolbox more versatile.   The idea of creating this course was born back in early 2021 when one of Yaro's students @@StartBracket@@rated around 2000 USCF@@EndBracket@@ asked him: 'Can you show me something that is simple and doesn't require too much time to memorize since I'm too busy managing my business?'. After some thinking, 1. Nf3 came to mind. Even if you forget a move or two - no worries, you would still have a nice playable position! That's not the case in the sharpest lines of 1. e4, for example.   Being busy coaching many students and having little to none of the free time ourselves, we have started employing 1. Nf3 on a regular basis even in the most important tournaments @@StartBracket@@including the World Cup 2021 and numerous GM-norm events@@EndBracket@@. Without further ado, let's get started! }
