{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 b6 { Leads to all four bishops being fianchetto-d! } 5. Bg2
Bb7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4
{ We like keeping the d and e pawns on their initial positions for extra flexibility in the future. }
7... c5 8. d4
{ Pretty much the only sensible idea. White needs to clear the d-file for the rooks. }
8... cxd4 9. Qxd4
{ It looks scary to get the queen out so soon but the risks are well-calculated. White can't trade the light-squared bishops just yet. }
9... Nc6 10. Qc3 Rc8 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Qe1
{ The queen is getting out of the way after the f1-rook takes its place on d1. }
12... Qb8 13. Nc3 Rfd8 14. Rac1
{ We were following the game Aronian - Vachier Lagrave, Leuven 2017. Plan: e4, Qe2, and then Nd5 eventually. White is significantly better due to spacial advantage + Black has zero targets. }
