1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. c4
{ We need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP bishop on b2. }
6... c6 7. O-O Nbd7
{ This weak move is the most frequent guest in the games on lichess.org @@StartBracket@@3.9 billion game database speaks for itself@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4
{ Stopping Black from going e7-e5! We are surely aware that this move opens the square on e4 for the knight on f6. Well, we will be able to get rid of that knight on e4 easily by moving away the knight on f3 @@StartBracket@@most likely, to e5@@EndBracket@@ and playing f2-f3! }
8... Ne4 9. e3 { Reinforcing our d4-pawn. } 9... Ndf6 10. Ne5
{ f2-f3 is coming and our chances of getting rid of the knight on e4 are safely estimated at 99.99%. To learn more, please refer to the line in chapter 1.2. }
