{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. c4
{ We need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP bishop on b2. }
6... c6 7. O-O Bg4 8. d3
{ As usual, the pawn goes to d3 after the Black's bishop appearance on g4. Generally when Black develops the bishop on f5 or g4, putting the pawn on d3 controls the e4-square and restricts the opponent's bishop. }
8... Nbd7 9. Nbd2 Re8
{ 9...a5  10.h3  Getting that light-squared bishop no matter what.  10...Bxf3  11.Nxf3⩲  We do the same thing as usual: a3, e3, b4, Qe2, Rac1, Rfd1. }
10. h3
{ It makes sense to attack the bishop and get a bishop pair advantage after they trade on f3. Other retreats don't work: if Bh5, then g4 traps the bishop; Bf5 or Be6 falls into Nd4 and the bishop is gonna be traded and the pawn structure is going to be better for White. }
10... Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e5 12. cxd5 { Opens up the c-file for our rook. } 12...
cxd5 13. Rc1
{ Despite the looks, Black's pawn center is not as good as it may seem at the first glance.   1@@EndBracket@@ If the d-pawn moves --> the bishop on g2 becomes too active.   2@@EndBracket@@ If the e-pawn moves --> the bishop on b2 becomes quite unpleasant for Black as well. }
13... Qa5 14. a3 e4 { 14...Qb6  15.b4⩲  preparing Qb3. } 15. dxe4 Nxe4
{ 15...dxe4  16.Nd2±  Resembles the positions we have considered previously and still is much worse for Black. }
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Ndf6 18. Qb2 { Defense of the a3-pawn is necessary. }
18... Rac8 19. e3
{ Making sure the d5 doesn't go anywhere and keeping our e2 pawn safe and sound on e3. We will continue with b4 and Nd4, and the plan will be: Rfd1 and, at some point, Nd4-e2-f4! }
