1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6
{ By far, the most frequent move on lichess.org. } 6. d4
{ We can't let Black go e7-e5 on the next move or else the entire system makes no sense! @@StartBracket@@RIP, bishop on b2@@EndBracket@@. We got some good news for you: if you remember to play 6. d4, you are better than over 70% of players on lichess.org @@StartBracket@@this move was played in only 29.6% of the games, while the rest of the players were happily unaware of Black's plans@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nbd7
{ Again, the most frequent move on lichess.org. We cover almost everything under the sun besides ...Nbd7 in the main part of the course. }
7. O-O Re8 8. a4
{ White grabs some space on the queenside. Guess what, the queenside will be our main playground. Now, make sure to study the chapters and especially pay attention to the game played by Kramnik vs. Demchenko in the Model Games chapter. You will learn everything you need to know there. }
