{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 b6
{ Welcome to the copycat line! Usually employed by the players who like fiancetto, Queen's Indian setups, or lack imagination :@@EndBracket@@ }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. g3 e6
{ 4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  b6  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 c5 8. d4 cxd4
{ 8...d5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Nbd2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.b3  b6  3.Bb2  Bb7  4.g3  e6  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  d5  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.d4  c5  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Nbd2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qf4 { The best square for the queen. } 10... d5 11. Rd1
{ We need to anticipate well in advance which files can be open in the middlegame. With a high degree of certainty, we are betting on d- and c-files, hence the rooks should go on d1 and c1. }
11... Qc8 12. Nc3
{ We need to finish our queenside development and bring the rook from a1 to c1 in the future. }
12... dxc4 13. Qxc4
{ The only recaprute that makes sense. Taking with the b3 pawn would only create a weak isolani on c4, and Black could have exploited it with moves like Na5. }
13... Nb4 14. Ne5
{ Trading the light square bishops helps us gain more control over Black's queenside and potentially establish an outpost for the knight on c6. }
14... Bxg2 15. Qxc8 Raxc8 16. Kxg2
{ White is a tiny bit better and has absolutely no risk of losing. The plan: Rac1, a3, b4, Nb5. The money square: c6. If you get your knight there, you should have no issues winning the game. }
