{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 d5
{ This move was played 32% of the time after 1.Nf3 on lichess.org. To our big surprise, 1... Nf6 is the second most frequent move but only at 16%! So, the chances for an average player to see 1... d5 are double those of 1... Nf6. }
2. b3 Bf5 3. Bb2 e6
{ 3...Nd7  4.d3  Ngf6  5.Nbd2  e6  6.g3  Be7  7.Bg2  O-O  8.O-O  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/8/1P3N2/PBPPPPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.g3  Nf6  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.d3  Nbd7  8.Nbd2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   3...f6  makes no sense because of  4.d4  and the pawn on f6 turns out to be punishing its own friendly knight on g8 while contributing nothing to the game. }
4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Be7
{ 5...c6  6.O-O  h6  7.d3  Be7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c4  Bh7  10.a3  a5  11.Qc2  Nbd7  12.Ne5  transposes to the mainline.   5...h6  6.O-O  Be7  7.d3  O-O  8.Nbd2  also transposes to the mainline. }
6. O-O O-O 7. d3
{ Whenever you see the bishop on f5, play d3. White's plan is to limit the bishop on f5, play Nbd2 and get e2-e4 going at some point. }
7... h6 8. Nbd2 Bh7
{ 8...Nbd7  9.c4  c6  10.a3  a5  11.Qc2  transposes to the mainline.   8...c6  9.c4  Nbd7  10.a3  a5  11.Qc2  Bh7  12.Ne5  also transposes to the mainline.   8...a5  9.a3  a4?!  The following game is Yaro's win at the World Cup 2021. As you can see, we truly believe in what we recommend and employ all those lines ourselves! The whole game follows: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Zherebukh,Y @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@-Ioannidis, E @@StartBracket@@2422@@EndBracket@@ Krasnaya Polyana 2021. }
9. c4
{ What we are doing, setting up this pawns chain e2-d3-c4, is keeping the bishop on h7 locked out of the game, trying to play mainly on the queenside. }
9... c6 10. a3
{ As usual, we would like to expand on the queenside with b3-b4. } 10... a5 11.
Qc2 { The idea is to go Bc3 and then Qb2. } 11... Nbd7 12. Ne5
{ Our knight is somewhat in the way of our bishop on g2 and is not attacking anything. So once the opponent puts the knight on d7, we are happy to exchange it with Ne5. }
12... Nxe5
{ 12...Re8  13.Nxd7  Nxd7  14.Bc3  The plan: b4, Qb2, and attack on the queenside.   12...Rc8  13.Nxd7  Nxd7  14.b4!⩲  works out for the same reasons as in the 12... Bd6 line. }
13. Bxe5
{ If  13...Nd7  14.Bc3  Bf6  15.b4  Bxc3  16.Qxc3⩲  The plan: Rab1, Rfc1, b5, c5. You can train the full line here. }
