{ This move was played 32% of the time after 1.Nf3 on lichess.org. To our big surprise, 1... Nf6 is the second most frequent move but only at 16%! So, the chances for an average player to see 1... d5 are double those of 1... Nf6. }
2. b3 Bg4
{ One of the most active systems for Black. As compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  Bf5  ,  the bishop can't be attacked with e4 later in the opening. }
3. Bb2 Nd7
{ The most-played move at the master level. Black will now continue with ...Ngf6, ...e6 followed by ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
4. g3 Bxf3 { Black gives up the bishop pair to spoil our pawn structure. } 5.
exf3 Ngf6 6. Bg2 g6 7. f4 e6 { 7...Bg7?  loses a pawn.  8.Bxd5! } 8. O-O Bg7 9.
d4
{ A multi-purpose move: White is preventing a potential dark-square bishop trade and getting ready to get the knight to d2 and e5. Tip: Having both bishops is the ideal scenario. However, if you find yourself trading the b2-bishop, don't panic. You can still have a great position if you manage to get the knight to the e5 and if you play c2-c4 with the idea to open up your bishop on g2. }
9... O-O 10. Nd2
{ The knight enters the game preparing to reach the outpost with d2-f3-e5. }
10... c6 11. c4 Re8 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Re1 a5 14. a4
{ a3 with the idea of b4 was also playable. } 14... h5 15. Nf3
{ The knight is going to e5 as usual. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends with this move. You can study our full analysis here. }
