1. Nf3 d5
{ This move was played 32% of the time after 1.Nf3 on lichess.org. To our big surprise, 1... Nf6 is the second most frequent move but only at 16%! So, the chances for an average player to see 1... d5 are double those of 1... Nf6. }
2. b3 Bg4
{ One of the most active systems for Black. As compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  Bf5  ,  the bishop can't be attacked with e4 later in the opening. }
3. Bb2 Nd7
{ The most-played move at the master level. Black will now continue with ...Ngf6, ...e6 followed by ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
4. g3 Ngf6 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6
{ 7...e5?  exposes Black's center a bit too soon. } 8. d4
{ Whenever the bishop is on g4 --> Put the pawn on d4 and try to occupy the e5 square with the knight on f3. }
8... O-O 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Nd2 Qe7
{ 10...Qc7  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.f3  is the same as @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3pNb2/2PP4/1P4P1/PB1NPPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qe7  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.f3  . }
11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. f3
{ Quite often, aiming for e4 and space control is the only sensible idea. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends with this move. You can study our full analysis here. }
