{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 d5
{ This move was played 32% of the time after 1.Nf3 on lichess.org. To our big surprise, 1... Nf6 is the second most frequent move but only at 16%! So, the chances for an average player to see 1... d5 are double those of 1... Nf6. }
2. b3 c5 3. e3
{ The only move!  3.Bb2?!  doesn't work because of  3...f6!  and nothing can prevent Black from going ...e5 the next move. }
3... Nc6
{ •  3...f6  4.d4!  cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.Bb2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  f6  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   •  3...a6  4.Bb2  Nc6  5.d4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  a6  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Bb2 Nf6 5. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight and winning a tempo since Black pretty much has to play Bd7 or otherwise face consequences of a damaged pawn structure after Bb5-c6. }
5... Bd7
{ •  5...a6  Wastes a tempo. Black is forcing us to do what want to do anyway.  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.Ne5±   •  5...Qc7  Makes even less sense than  5...Qb6  .  6.c4  a6  7.Be5  Qb6  8.Ba4±  The queen moves to c7 and b6 proved to be a waste of time. }
6. O-O e6 7. d4
{ The only sensible way to fight for the center. It wouldn't make too much sense to play d3 since Black would be happy to play Bd6, castle, and eventually prepare e6-e5, winning all available space in the center. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4
{ We do not take with the knight for two reasons. First, we have more control over the e5-square. Then, and more importantly, we prevent Black from getting rid of the bad bishop with  8.Nxd4  Nxd4  9.Bxd7+ }
8... Bd6 9. Bd3
{ The bishop may not be needed on b5 anymore. We should say it has done a great job: provoked ...Bd7 and ...e6, thus locking the bishop on d7 forever. }
9... O-O 10. c4 Nb4 11. Be2
{ Never gonna give you up, never gonna let you down... Yes, you just got rickrolled in a Chessable course for the first time ever :@@EndBracket@@ We firmly believe that chess and humor should coexist and make the game of chess fun to learn. }
11... Nc6 12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Re1 { Eventually making room for the bishop in f1. }
13... Re8 14. Bf1 { The plan: a3, Rac1, c5, b4. Attack on the queenside. } *

