{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 d5
{ This move was played 32% of the time after 1.Nf3 on lichess.org. To our big surprise, 1... Nf6 is the second most frequent move but only at 16%! So, the chances for an average player to see 1... d5 are double those of 1... Nf6. }
2. b3 c6
{ We don't spend time on this move separately in the course since, at best for Black, it will transpose to the other lines @@StartBracket@@most notably, 2... Bf5 or 2... Bg4, covered in chapter 2.1 and chapter 2.2, respectively@@EndBracket@@. Since it was played a bit on lichess.org, we will provide a little bit of an overview here for the lines that don't transpose to the lines in the course. }
3. Bb2 Nf6 4. g3
{ We still would like to fianchetto the bishop on g2. It doesn't really make sense to us to place the bishop on e2 after 4. e3 since we only do it in some lines where Black plays early 1... d5 and 2... c5. We are obliged to play 3. e3 there since 3. Bb2 runs into f6, which effectively destroys the bishop @@StartBracket@@4... e5 is Black's next move@@EndBracket@@. }
4... e6
{ Other moves transpose to the lines we have looked at in the course. This odd move was played shockingly frequently - almost 13% of the time, while the top move 3... Bg4 is at almost 31%. }
5. Bg2 Be7
{ Played over 50% of the time and easily beat the other moves in terms of frequency. }
6. O-O O-O 7. d3
{ Playing d4 would be awful - the Black's knight would establish an outpost on e4. }
7... Nbd7 8. Nbd2
{ White is already much better @@StartBracket@@what is the bishop on c8 doing with its life?@@EndBracket@@. Our plan is straightforward - push e4, play Qe2, and then expand further with e5, d4, c4. }
