{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 c5
{ After boldly landing your knight on f3, you may face 1... c5 if you face anybody who would ordinarily play Sicilian Defense vs. 1. e4. We would not advise going 2. e4 in this instance since it will open up a completely new can of worms - about 12495837 lines of Sicilian Defense. Okay, we have to admit that the number is completely made up.  However, you get the point - you wouldn't want to memorize countless Sicilians and we wouldn't want to write about them @@StartBracket@@not until the next year at least!@@EndBracket@@. Instead, move your pawn to b3! This chapter will expose some of the interesting ideas in a pure English Opening - it's when we put the pawn on c4 and Black eventually responds with e5. }
2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 e6 4. e4 { One of the very few cases when e4 is possible. }
4... a6 5. c4 { Stopping d5 and threatening d4. } 5... Nf6
{ 5...Qc7  6.Bd3!?  The plan: O-O, e5, Qe2, Nc3-e4. Attack on the kingside. }
6. e5 Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. Nc3 { Aiming for Ne4. } 8... d6
{ 8...Nf5  9.Bd3  Asking the knight to leave and proceeding with the expected Ne4.  9...Nfd4  10.Ne4⩲ }
9. d4
{ A pawn sacrifice! Our plan is to castle long as soon as possible and then expand on the kingside with h4 and g3. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxe5 11. Qd2 { Preparing to castle on the queenside. } 11...
Be7 12. O-O-O Ng6 13. Kb1
{ A standard move, happening 90% of the time when the Grandmasters long castle. }
13... O-O 14. g3 Bd7 15. h4
{ Black might be up a pawn but our space advantage more than compensates for it. Our plan would be Bg2 and f4, h5, aiming to squeeze Black out to the last two ranks. }
