1. Nf3 c5
{ After boldly landing your knight on f3, you may face 1... c5 if you face anybody who would ordinarily play Sicilian Defense vs. 1. e4. We would not advise going 2. e4 in this instance since it will open up a completely new can of worms - about 12495837 lines of Sicilian Defense. Okay, we have to admit that the number is completely made up.  However, you get the point - you wouldn't want to memorize countless Sicilians and we wouldn't want to write about them @@StartBracket@@not until the next year at least!@@EndBracket@@. Instead, move your pawn to b3! This chapter will expose some of the interesting ideas in a pure English Opening - it's when we put the pawn on c4 and Black eventually responds with e5. }
2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d6
{ •  3...Nf6  4.e3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.b3  c5  3.Bb2  Nc6  4.e3  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   •  3...d5  4.e3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  c5  3.e3  Nc6  4.Bb2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. g3
{ Going for a double fianchetto, followed by c4 and e4. } 6... g6
{ Played almost twice as frequently on lichess.org compared to the main move 6... e5, which is covered starting from here. }
7. Bg2 Bd7
{ Black obviously needs to protect the knight, right? Well, we were shocked to learn that Black managed to do something different @@StartBracket@@and much worse!@@EndBracket@@ almost 54% of the time on lichess.org. When you play an average player, you never know what to expect. The point of the story: it's way more important to internalize the plans and the ideas than memorize everything and understand nothing. }
8. O-O Bg7 9. c4
{ Leads us to a comfortable Maroczy bind pawn structure. You may ask who's Maroczy, is he like a famous streamer? Not exactly. To our limited knowledge, he was one the strongest players in the early 1900s and apparently a guy who really liked his pawns on c4 and e4. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3
{ This move was employed by GM Svidler. You may study his game in the Model Games chapter for more details. We also have a similar model game by GM Vitiugov in the same chapter. }
