{ After boldly landing your knight on f3, you may face 1... c5 if you face anybody who would ordinarily play Sicilian Defense vs. 1. e4. We would not advise going 2. e4 in this instance since it will open up a completely new can of worms - about 12495837 lines of Sicilian Defense. Okay, we have to admit that the number is completely made up.  However, you get the point - you wouldn't want to memorize countless Sicilians and we wouldn't want to write about them @@StartBracket@@not until the next year at least!@@EndBracket@@. Instead, move your pawn to b3! This chapter will expose some of the interesting ideas in a pure English Opening - it's when we put the pawn on c4 and Black eventually responds with e5. }
2. b3 d6
{ •  2...d5  3.e3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  c5  3.e3  @@StartBracket@@see the chapter@@EndBracket@@.   •  2...Nf6  3.Bb2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.b3  c5  3.Bb2  @@StartBracket@@see the chapter@@EndBracket@@. }
3. c4
{ Other moves don't look as promising to us. The central pawn configuration can be quite different in this section of the course compared to others. }
3... e5 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. g3 g6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O
{ No need to play Bb2 just yet as it's too early to tell if we need the bishop there or not. }
7... Nf6 8. d3 O-O 9. Rb1
{ We are preparing a3-b4 and will be developing the bishop to g5. } 9... a6 10.
a3 Rb8 { Black is ready to meet b4 with the capture on b4, followed by b5. }
11. Bg5
{ Whenever we can, we should trade the dark-squared bishop for the knight. The reason: we don't really use the dark-squared bishop all that much while Black can use the kingside knight for the attack on our king. }
11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. b4
{ The plan: Nd2, Nd5, pressure on the b-file and h1-a8 diagonal. } *

