1. Nf3 g6
{ We know quite a few people who play 1... g6 pretty much against anything. In our not-so-humble opinion, 2. e4 will wreck their defenses and inflict severe pain on the Black's king. Chapter 4.1 will cover 2...Bg7, which leads to Pirc/ Modern Defense type of positions, 4.2 and 4.3 will deal with 2... c5, which may lead to a rare line of Pirc or Accelerated Dragon variation of Sicilian Defense.  Arguably, 1... g6 is one of the worst moves out there against 1. Nf3. Black simply gives away too much space in the middle. }
2. e4
{ We must bite the bullet, take a deep breath, and go e4 as soon as on move 2! }
2... Bg7 3. d4 d6
{ 3...c5  4.dxc5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  c5  3.d4  Bg7  4.dxc5  which is covered in chapter 4.2. }
4. Bc4
{ The most natural development, employing the bishop on the most dangerous a2-g8 diagonal and eyeing the f7 pawn. }
4... Nf6 5. Qe2
{ Another crucial move to remember. The queen will support our e4 pawn nicely and might help with a typical e4-e5 pawn break in the center. }
5... O-O 6. O-O Nc6
{ We have included two most common moves on lichess.org in this Quick Starter chapter - 6... Bg4 and 6... Nc6. To get familiar with other options that could be employed by Black, please refer to the full Chapter 4.1 in the course.  Hikaru Nakamura did a splendid job of getting all of his pieces in the game as soon as possible and then utilizing them to the maximum. You can see the full game shown as a clickable line here. }
7. e5 dxe5
{ 7...Ng4  is covered here, while  7...Nh5  is analyzed in this line. } 8. dxe5
Ng4 9. Rd1 { Attacking the queen and improving the rook. } 9... Qe8 10. Bf4
{ The plan: h3, Nc3, Nd5 or Nb5. } *

