1. Nf3 g6
{ We know quite a few people who play 1... g6 pretty much against anything. In our not-so-humble opinion, 2. e4 will wreck their defenses and inflict severe pain on the Black's king. Chapter 4.1 will cover 2...Bg7, which leads to Pirc/ Modern Defense type of positions, 4.2 and 4.3 will deal with 2... c5, which may lead to a rare line of Pirc or Accelerated Dragon variation of Sicilian Defense.  Arguably, 1... g6 is one of the worst moves out there against 1. Nf3. Black simply gives away too much space in the middle. }
2. e4
{ We must bite the bullet, take a deep breath, and go e4 as soon as on move 2! }
2... c5
{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until the few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 Bg7 4. dxc5 Qa5+ { The only feasible way to get the pawn back } 5. c3
Qxc5 6. Na3
{ The knight on the rim is not always dim. Here, we are aiming for Be3 and Nb5. }
6... d6 7. Nb5 a6
{ 7...Nf6  just loses the pawn on a7 without any compensation.  8.Be3  Qc6  9.Nxa7+- }
8. Be3 Qc6 9. Na7
{ A nice double attack from a highly unsual position for a knight. } 9... Qc7
10. Nxc8 Qxc8 11. Nd2 Nf6 12. g3
{ A slightly unusual fiancetto. We believe the bishop on g2 is in a better position to support our kingside expansion as opposed to e2 or d3. }
12... O-O 13. Bg2 Nbd7 14. O-O
{ Plan: f4, h3, g4, Qf3, Rf2, Raf1, and attack on the kingside. } *

