1. Nf3 d6
{ Part 5 will cover White's best responses vs. 1... d6. The important thing to remember is to play 2. d4, stopping Black from gaining too much space with e5. We offer a unique way of playing with 2... Nf6 @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3@@EndBracket@@, which will please anybody looking to escape the rut of the regular openings like King's Indian Defense. You will also see an unconventional way of playing vs. Philidor's Defense @@StartBracket@@that's right!@@EndBracket@@ with Carlsen's favorite @@StartBracket@@at least on lichess.org@@EndBracket@@ 5. Rg1, followed by 6. g4. While we try to stay unbiased, chapter 5 was the most fun one to write! }
2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... f5 3. Nc3
{ We could also follow a setup suggested in 1... f5  chapter by playing 3. b3. However, we believe 3. Nc3 might be an even better option, enabling us to long castle rather quickly. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. Qd3
{ That's why we prefer the 3. Nc3 system in this move order. The queen attacks f5, supports e4, and prepares O-O-O. What's not to like, right? }
5... g6
{ •  5...h6  6.Bd2  Of course, not trading on f6.  6...e6  7.e4±   •  5...e6  6.e4  A great correspondence game @@StartBracket@@read: humans-using-top-engines game@@EndBracket@@, illustrating the drawbacks of 5... e6. You will see the first 14 moves here. For the complete game, please check Model Games chapter related to 1... d6.  6...fxe4  7.Nxe4  Be7  8.Bd2  Nxe4  9.Qxe4  Nf6  10.Qe3  Nd5  11.Qb3  O-O  12.c4  Nf4  13.g3  Ng6  14.h4!±  1-0 Peigney,C @@StartBracket@@2325@@EndBracket@@ -Andersen,J @@StartBracket@@2307@@EndBracket@@, ICCF email 2014. White is in great shape, threatening h5. }
6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4 Bg7 8. O-O-O
{ The game here is a no-brainer: push h4 and attack. } 8... Nxe4
{ 8...O-O  Ng3  Avoiding the trade on e4 and keeping Black wondering what to do about the knights fighting for f6. }
9. Qxe4 Nf6 10. Qe3 { The plan: h4, Bc4, h5. } *

