{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 d6
{ Part 5 will cover White's best responses vs. 1... d6. The important thing to remember is to play 2. d4, stopping Black from gaining too much space with e5. We offer a unique way of playing with 2... Nf6 @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3@@EndBracket@@, which will please anybody looking to escape the rut of the regular openings like King's Indian Defense. You will also see an unconventional way of playing vs. Philidor's Defense @@StartBracket@@that's right!@@EndBracket@@ with Carlsen's favorite @@StartBracket@@at least on lichess.org@@EndBracket@@ 5. Rg1, followed by 6. g4. While we try to stay unbiased, chapter 5 was the most fun one to write! }
2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...g6  3.e4  Bg7  @@StartBracket@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  Bg7  3.d4  d6  4.Bc4 }
3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. e4 e5
{ We are now in Phillidor's Defense domain. Our suggestion here is a far less explored line, leading to some sharp and active chess. }
5. Rg1
{ We have noticed this move while studying DrNykerstein games on lichess.org @@StartBracket@@allegedly, Magnus Carlsen's account@@EndBracket@@. White's idea is exactly what appears to be - g4! }
5... g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. g4 O-O 9. Qd2
{ Going for the long castle, as usual. } 9... c6 10. O-O-O Qe7 11. Qd6
{ We have seen this queen trade before. The endgame is the best risk-free way to pressure your opponent. }
11... Qxd6 12. Rxd6 Re8 13. g5
{ We need to push the knight on the outskirts, far away from the queenside events. }
13... Nh5 14. Rd1 { The rook on d6 will soon be replaced with the knight. }
14... Bf8 15. Nd2 Nb6 16. Nb3 { The plan: a4, a5. Attack on the queenside. } *

