2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...g6  3.e4  Bg7  @@StartBracket@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  Bg7  3.d4  d6  4.Bc4 }
3. Nc3 g6 4. e4 Bg7 5. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4 in advance. } 5... O-O 6. Bd3 Nbd7
{ The second most common move here, according to an online lichess.org database. }
7. e5 { Playing e5 while we can! } 7... dxe5
{ 7...Ne8  8.e6!  Removes the pawn on f7 from the king and makes the g6-pawn far more susceptible to the kingside attack. You can see the full line here. }
8. dxe5 Ne8 9. Bc4 { The pawn on e5 is safe because of the pin on the d-file. }
9... c6 10. e6
{ We need to break Black's pawn structure before they catch up and play Nc7 or e6, stopping us from playing e6 forever. }
10... fxe6 11. Bxe6+ Kh8 12. O-O
{ We have a solid edge here due to a safer king and a better pawn structure. Black's isolated and blocked pawn on e7 may eventually fall if we press hard enough: Qe2, Re1, Bg5, Rad1. }
