1. Nf3
{ We will now consider Dutch-related structures arising after 1... f5. We recommend sticking with 2. b3 - our favorite bishop fianchetto. One major takeaway from this chapter: always aim to break in the center with e4! We especially recommend studying the game after 8. c4 closely. To make these lines more digestible for the learners, we have split them into two parts - chapter 6.1 and chapter 6.2. }
1... f5
{ You know what's crazy? An average player on lichess.org blunders a pawn after 1... e5 three times more often  (!!)  than plays a normal-looking 1... f5! We still encourage you to learn how to handle 1... f5 since it can be played by anybody who likes Dutch Defense. }
2. b3 d6
{ Most of the time this move transposes to 2...Nf6. We will look into the lines that are not related. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 5. e3
{ The bishop usually needs to stay away from g2 because Black may be able to push e5-e4 and make it highly ineffective. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c6
{ 7...a5  8.c4  c6  9.Qc2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1p1bp/3p1np1/5p2/3P4/1P2PN2/PBP1BPPP/RN1Q1RK1 b - - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7...c6  8.c4  a5  9.Qc2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
8. c4 Qe8 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 e5
{ Black has a tiny opportunity window for this break; otherwise, we would push e4. }
11. dxe5 dxe5 12. c5
{ Securing the outpost on d6. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends with this move. You can study our full analysis here. }
