{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide! This chapter will contain trainable lines from the seven sections of the course. We have also included an overview of the most commonly played moves on Lichess.org, according to their now almost 3.9-billion-game database as of February 2023. You read that right - it's 3.9 billion with a 'b'! We would have never imagined that such large datasets would exist one day.   Our goal in this Quickstarter chapter is to provide the learners with a quick overview of the highlights of the course. If you need to review the content before the game and have a limited time for preparation, this chapter is your best friend.   A word of caution: this chapter is meant to provide a simple overview of the main lines in the majority of the chapters while omitting plenty of variations and granular details that will make you an expert in 1. Nf3. Please make sure to study the main content and all trainable lines in this course whenever you have some free time. Good luck on your journey and remember to have fun while studying! }
1. Nf3 Nc6
{ Have you expected to learn Chigorin Defense in this course? Neither have we expected to write about it :@@EndBracket@@ After  1...Nc6  , White's best option is to play  2.d4  @@StartBracket@@stopping Black from playing e5 is crucial@@EndBracket@@. We would recommend primarily focusing on 3... Bg4. In some cases, we get double pawns on the f-file, which will help us fight for the center and attack on the g-file.   In the main line, we leave the king in the center for an extended time, since it's the safest behind the pawn wall. The 3... Nf6 line would require a bit of memorization - but once you learn it, you may get a winning position almost right out of the opening. }
2. d4
{ We transpose to the Chigorin Defense, rarely played on a high level.   2.b3?!  doesn't make much sense anymore since Black can easily grab some space after  2...e5  3.Bb2  e4  4.Nd4  Nxd4  5.Bxd4  d5  6.e3 }
2... d5 3. c4 Bg4 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3
{ 5.dxc6?!  Bxc6  6.Nc3  e6  and Black has a strong bishop controlling the c6-g2 diagonal. }
5... Qxd5 6. e3 e5 { Attempting to break our center. } 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3
{ Otherwise, White would be practically winning after d5 and a3. } 9. bxc3 Qd6
10. Rb1
{ White's pawn center is so powerful that the short castle is not even necessary - the king is perfectly safe on e1. }
10... b6
{ 10...Rb8  11.Rg1  g6  12.f4  exf4  13.e4±  was played in the game Jumabayev,R @@StartBracket@@2615@@EndBracket@@-Yakubboev,N @@StartBracket@@2600@@EndBracket@@, Tashkent 2019. }
11. Rg1 g6 12. f4
{ A temporary pawn sacrifice with the idea to undouble the pawns on the f-file. }
12... exf4 13. e4 O-O-O 14. e5 Qe6 15. Qg4
{ Trading queens is one the best things you can do whenever you have a better pawn structure. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends with this move. You can study our full analysis here. }
