{ The most direct way to refute Black's questionable opening strategy. } 2...
Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...c5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p1pppppp/1p6/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq e3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bb7  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. d4 Bb4
{ •  4...c5  5.d5±  Kills the bishop. The plan is the usual Be3, Qd2, O-O-O.   •  4...g6  5.Bg5  ruins Black's plans for ...Bg7.  5...Be7  6.h4±   •  4...Ne7  5.d5  Ng6  6.h4!±  The plan: h5 @@StartBracket@@if Black allows@@EndBracket@@, Bg5, Qd2, O-O-O. }
5. Bd3 Nf6 6. Nd2
{ The best defense of the e4. Also, played in only 0.5% of the games that got to this point on lichess.org. Congrats, you have just made it to the top 1%! :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... d5 7. e5 Ne4 8. Qg4 Kf8
{ 8...Qg5  doesn't provide any relief.  9.Qxg5  Nxg5  10.Nb5±  Black still needs to deal with the lack of space and targets. }
9. Ncb1 { Whatever it takes to play c3! } 9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 Be7 11. c3 c5 12.
O-O
{ White has a safer king, better pieces, and a strong center. The plan: @@StartBracket@@if Black goes Nc6 next@@EndBracket@@ Nf3, Be3, Nd2, f4. Attack on the kingside. }
