1. Nf3 b5
{ One of least challenging moves. No wonder the chapter dedicated to 1... b5 is going to be the shortest. Our path to advantage is crystal clear. }
2. e4 Bb7 { We will consider the most principled and aggressive approach. } 3.
Bxb5 Bxe4 4. O-O
{ We know that we need to castle for sure. Everything is secondary and can played later. First things first. }
4... Nf6 5. d4 e6 6. c4 { Grabbing all the space we can. } 6... Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7
8. Re1 O-O 9. Ba4
{ The bishop on b5 is useless, so we transfer it to a4 and later to c2 if the need arises. }
9... d6 10. d5 e5 11. c5
{ The key move, making this whole line with b5, Bb7, and Be4 unplayable. }
11... c6 12. Qb3 { The queen effectively comes into the game. } 12... Qc8 13.
cxd6
{ Opening up the files and getting ready for Ne5, Bg5, and Rac1. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends with this move. You can study our full analysis here. }
