[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to Part One"]
[Black "Introduction to Part One"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ One of the best players in the early 1900s and the inventor of a Reti Opening - Richard Reti - would have been proud to see his brainchild not only survive the test of time but also be recommended as one of the most promising opening weapons more than 100 years later, in 2023.   One of the most significant merits of early knight development is having the flexibility to decide later what to do with the central pawns, which leaves us plenty of room for creativity: we can do d3-e4, d4-e4, c4-d3 and leave the pawn on e2; we can always adjust based on our opponent's moves. In addition, this move is considered one of the safest openings for White, especially when White later continues with g3, Bg2, O-O and builds an unbreakable fortress for the king. }
1... Nf6
{ We bet you might be seeing  1...Nf6  the most.  This move might be favored by anybody who plays any opening related to the bishop fianchetto to g7 after g6, like King's Indian Defense, Gruenfeld, Benoni, Benko, etc. It may also be played whenever Black wants to leave you in a dark about their further plans and wants to be just as flexible as White. }
2. b3 g6
{ Black intends to fianchetto the bishop to g7, which helps them fight against our bishop on b2.   •  2...c5  Our prediction: if somebody normally plays c5 against 1. c4, they may opt to playing c5 against 1. Nf3-2. b3 as well.  3.Bb2  e6  Apart from this move, we would also recommend studying how to play versus 3... Nc6, which is the second most challenging move for White.  4.g3  d5  5.Bg2  Nc6  6.O-O  Be7  7.e3  We will prepare d2-d4 and c2-c4 a bit later. Pushing the pawn to e3 here makes sense. When we go d2-d4 and they capture on d4, we would have e3xd4, which will provide us with an outpost on e5 for our knight on f3. We will examine this unique setup in chapter 1.1.   •  2...e6  3.Bb2  d5  4.c4!  As usual, we would need to prevent Black from playing c7-c5 and then d5-d4, effectively neutralizing our pride - the bishop on b2. Please see chapter 1.2 for more details. We would also recommend studying masterpieces by Hikaru Nakamura in the Model Games chapter at the end of the course.   •  2...b6  This leads to a 'copycat' line as we call it later in the course.  3.Bb2  Bb7  4.g3  e6  Black, of course, can also play 4... g6. It transposes to the lines covered in Chapter 1 with a slightly different move order @@StartBracket@@see 4... b6 line in Chapter 1.1@@EndBracket@@.  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  We are getting ready to push d2-d4. The bishop on e7 is not as well placed as on g7, so overall we consider this setup being an improvement for White compared to the 4-bishop fianchetto considered in Chapter 1.1. To learn more about how to get an edge here, please refer to chapter 1.3. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3
{ We like a double fianchetto the most. The bishops on b2 and g2 will be effectively working together on the longest diagonals, a1-h8 and h1-a8. }
4... O-O
{ 4...b6  Black aims to counter our bishop on g2 with their bishop on b7. We will break the symmetry a bit later in the game, often leading to a Maroczy bind type of game.  5.Bg2  Bb7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  The usual approach here is to push d4 on the next move and control as much space in the center as possible. We will take a deep dive into this position in chapter 1.1. }
5. Bg2 d5
{ •  5...d6  This move might be frequently employed by the King's Indian Defense players, who may strive to play e7-e5 next and get into familiar territory.  6.d4!  We need to nip Black's plans in the bud. No more e5! To see how to get a better game after Black still tries to play ...e5 @@StartBracket@@and for other details as well@@EndBracket@@, please refer to chapter 1.1.   •  5...c5  6.c4!  Stopping Black from playing d7-d5 and then d4. Chapter 1.1 will show how White can get a comfortable advantage. }
6. c4
{ A key move to remember in chapter 1.1! If we short castle instead, Black gets a better game by smothering our bishop after c7-c5 and then d5-d4. }
*

