1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. d4
{ Can't let ...e5 happen or else the bishop on b2 is dead. } 6... c5 7. c4
{ Prevents d5, just in case. Mindless  7.O-O  fails because of  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  d5! }
7... d5 8. Nbd2 cxd4 9. O-O
{ Delayed capture. White is waiting for Black to develop the knight on c6, so it can be taken after Nd4 e5.   9.Nxd4?  e5  and there is nothing for White to take on c6. }
9... Nc6 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 { 10...e5?  loses a pawn.  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bxe5+- }
11. Bxd4 Be6 12. c5
{ Adapting to changes, White transitions to a pure 3 vs. 2 pawn majority fight on the queenside. }
12... Qd7 13. Qc2 Rac8 14. Qb2
{ A useful maneveur, worth remembering. We will see it in the later chapters where Black's bishop appears on f5 and White's pawn is on d3. }
14... Bh3 15. b4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2
{ Plan: advance the pawns on the queenside and make sure to stop e5 by playing Nd2-f3. }
