[White "1.1) 1...Nf6 2.b3 g6: Black plays without ...d5"]
[Black "4...O-O 5.Bg2 d6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. d4
{ Can't let ...e5 happen or else the bishop on b2 is dead. } 6... c5 7. c4
{ Prevents d5, just in case. Mindless  7.O-O  fails because of  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  d5! }
7... Ne4
{ 7...Nc6?  doesn't make much sense since White simply gains a tempo and space after  8.d5± }
8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 { We must protect the d4-pawn. } 9... Bf5
{ The bishop is always a little off on f5. We just can't really tell what it is doing there. }
10. h3
{ Stops Bg4 @@StartBracket@@in case Black comes to their senses@@EndBracket@@ and creates a ghost threat of g4. Maybe we will play it, maybe not. Black now has to watch out. }
10... Rc8 11. Qe2 d5 12. Rd1
{ The rook on d1 makes a lot of sense. The X-ray on the Black's queen and the support of the center are the main ideas behind putting it on d1. }
12... dxc4 13. d5 { A pawn sacrifice, aimed to dominate the center! } 13...
Bxb2 14. Qxb2 Na5 15. Nfd2
{ A beautiful knight move, hitting the knight on e4 and preparing for e3-e4 pawn break if Black allows it. }
15... Nxd2 16. Nxd2 cxb3 17. axb3 Bd7 18. e4 { Dreams come true! } 18... b6 19.
e5 { The plan: Ne4, h4-h5-h6, d6. Dominate, attack, enjoy. } *

