1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. d4
{ Can't let ...e5 happen or else the bishop on b2 is dead. } 6... c5 7. c4
{ Prevents d5, just in case. Mindless  7.O-O  fails because of  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  d5! }
7... Ne4
{ 7...Nc6?  doesn't make much sense since White simply gains a tempo and space after  8.d5± }
8. O-O Nc6 9. e3 { We must protect the d4-pawn. } 9... Bg4 10. Qc1
{ Enables d4-d5 on the next move. Once the pawn is on d5 and the dark-squared bishops are traded, White can get the b1-knight out and start advancing the e-pawn by playing e4 and then e5. }
10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Ng5 12. Bxc6 { Obliterates Black's pawn structure. } 12...
bxc6 13. dxc5 Bxb2 14. Qxb2 dxc5 15. Nc3
{ We have almost finished our development but we still need to take care of the knight on g5. }
15... Qd3 16. h4 { So long, knight. } 16... Ne6 17. Rad1 Qf5 18. Qb1
{ It's always smart to trade queens in any strategically winning position --> it guarantees you won't blunder any random tactics and you're playing for 2 results. }
