[White "1.2) 1...Nf6 2.b3 g6: Black plays with ...d5"]
[Black "4...O-O 5.Bg2 d5 with 6...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. c4
{ Need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP b2-bishop. }
6... c5
{ Nowadays, Black tends to avoid this line altogether. The resulting endgame after  7...Nd5  is more depressing than the 2020 quarantine. }
7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd6 9. Rc1 { Eyeing the pawn on c5. } 9... Nc6 10. O-O b6
{ Otherwise, we would play Nb5 and collect the pawn on c5. } 11. d4
{ We should capitalize on the superiority of our light-squared bishop. } 11...
cxd4
{ 11...Nxd4  loses right away.  12.Nxd4  cxd4  13.Bxa8  dxc3  14.Qxd6  exd6  15.Bxc3+-  White is completely winning. }
12. Nb5 Qd7 13. Nbxd4 Bb7 14. Rxc6
{ A simple tactic that pretty much finishes the game in White's favor. } 14...
Bxc6 15. Ne5 Bxg2 { 15...Qc7  16.Nexc6+- } 16. Nxd7
{ White has a decisive material advantage and should simply trade pieces, aiming for a winning endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.2) 1...Nf6 2.b3 g6: Black plays with ...d5"]
[Black "4...O-O 5.Bg2 d5 with 6...c5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. c4
{ Need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP b2-bishop. }
6... c5
{ Nowadays, Black tends to avoid this line altogether. The resulting endgame after  7...Nd5  is more depressing than the 2020 quarantine. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. O-O Nc6 10. d4
{ We need to do this break before Black goes e5 and controls the center. }
10... cxd4
{ Not taking the pawn is even worse:  10...Qa5  11.e4  Nf6  12.d5  Rd8  13.Nbd2+- }
11. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ 11...Ndb4  12.Nxc6  Nxc6  13.Bxc6!  That's the endgame that is close to lost for Black. The knight typically dominates the bishop @@StartBracket@@especially, if the rooks are present@@EndBracket@@. I have provided a few model games below to illustrate how to win the ending.  13...bxc6  14.Qxd8  Rxd8  15.Nc3  Ba6   15...c5  16.Rfc1±  1-0 Burmakin, V @@StartBracket@@2578@@EndBracket@@ -Krassowizkij, J @@StartBracket@@2423@@EndBracket@@, Schwaebisch Gmuend 2015.  16.Rfd1±  1-0 Grandelius, N @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@-Grunberg, M @@StartBracket@@2401@@EndBracket@@, Tornelo INT 2020. }
12. Qxd4+ Nf6 13. Qe5
{ The bishop on g2 and the queen on e5 are incredibly effective. The main issue for Black is the lack of any meaningful plan and the crippled bishop on c8. }
13... a5
{ 13...Qd6  14.Qxd6  exd6  15.Nc3  Rd8  16.Rfd1±  The pawn on d6 is going to fall. It's only a matter of time. }
14. Nc3 Ra6 { Otherwise, Black can't get the rook in the game. } 15. Rfd1 Qe8
16. Nd5 Re6 17. Qb2 Rd6 18. Rd3
{ This move prepares to trade on f6 and avoid the rook trade on d1. } 18... Kg8
19. Nxf6+ Rxf6 20. Rc1
{ Sometimes, the Reti is all about the d- and c-file possession and the advantage of the g2-bishop over the c8-one. We were following the game Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2746@@EndBracket@@ -Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@, chess. com INT 2019. }
*

