1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. c4
{ Need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP b2-bishop. }
6... c6 7. O-O Nbd7
{ Truly puzzling. We honestly have no idea why would you block your bishop. Still, it's covered here for the sake of completness and because a few strong grand masters employed it before. }
8. d4 { Stopping e5. } 8... Ne4
{ Playing  8...b5  is also possible for Black but it is an incredibly rare choice. In response, I recommend you play  9.Nbd2  bxc4  10.bxc4  Rb8  11.Bc3  . We can look to play  Qa4  and  Rc1  next with some pressure towards black's c6-pawn. }
9. e3 Ndf6 10. Ne5 Bf5 11. f3
{ Starts an agressive push against Black's knight and the bishop on f5. } 11...
Nd6 12. g4 Be6
{ Taking the knight on b1 would only exacerbate Black's issues as they would have to deal with White's bishop pair in addition to lack of space. }
13. c5 Nde8 14. Nd2 Nd7 15. f4
{ We have all the space in the world. Plan: start advancing on the queenside as well, like b4, a4, b5! }
