{ Need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP b2-bishop. }
6... c6 7. O-O Bf5 8. d3
{ We will see even more cases where putting the pawn on d3 is super important whenever Black specifically has pawns on d5, c6, and the bishop on f5. }
8... Nbd7 9. Nbd2 Bg4
{ This is better but somehow played a lot less than ...Re8. } 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
Nxf3 Re8 12. Rc1
{ We don't want to play d4 since it gives away the e4 square for the Black's knight on f6. Once Black's knight is planted on e4, they can continue with f5, achieving a favorable stonewall-like structure without the painfully weak light-squared bishop like in Dutch Defense or some other openings. }
12... e5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e3 { The plan: a3-b4, Rc2, Qa1, Rfc1. } *

