6... c6 7. O-O a5 { Planning to go a4 and destabilize our queenside. } 8. Nc3
Ne4
{ 8...Na6  9.d4  Bf5  10.Rc1⩲  White has a tiny space advantage. Our plan could be e3, Qe2, Rad1.   8...Bg4  9.Ne5  Bf5  10.d4⩲  We will bring the rook to c1, Ba3, e3, Qe2, Rad1. }
9. Na4 Bxb2
{ If Black had instead played  9...b5  then we can respond with  10.Bxg7  Kxg7  11.Nb2  with the plan of playing Rc1, d3 kicking black's knight away, d4, Ne5 and Nbd3 to get a good grip on the center of the board. Black's queenside pawn structure would then be a bit compromised and especially the c6-pawn is a bit backward and weak. }
10. Nxb2
{ White is better since Black's king is compromised given the absence of the bishop on g7. Our plan is to play d3, kick the knight out, and then get a tight grip on the center by playing Qc2, e4 or d4, Nd3. }
