[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ Part 1 will feature the most common response, 1... Nf6. It could be played by a large number of players who would normally employ the following variety of openings against 1. d4: King's Indian Defense, Grunfeld, Benko, and Benoni among others. They could still have hopes of transposing to their 'native' repertoire and getting something similar and familiar vs. 1. Nf3. }
2. b3 g6
{ The most common response. It may be played by somebody who would ordinarily play any opening involving the bishop on g7. }
3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. c4
{ Need to challenge Black now! A huge mistake would have been  6.O-O?  c5!  7.c4  d4!  RIP b2-bishop. }
6... c6 7. O-O Bg4 8. d3
{ As usual, the pawn goes to d3 after the Black's bishop appearance on g4. }
8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nbd7 10. Qc2 e6 11. Nd2 Ne8 12. d4
{ We don't want to trade and get into a situation where they have 2 knights versus our knight and bishop. 2 knights, in general, are quite effective against a bishop and a knight. }
12... Nd6 13. e3 Re8 14. Bg2 h5
{ A psychological attack. The problem for Black is that they can't push any pawns @@StartBracket@@other than a or h@@EndBracket@@ without damaging its position. }
15. Nf3 Ne4 16. Ne1
{ The usual maneuver, aiming to push the knight away after f3. } 16... Ndf6 17.
Nd3 h4 18. f3 { Kicking that knight out! } 18... Nd6 19. Rae1
{ Bringing everybody to the party! } 19... hxg3 20. hxg3 Nf5 21. g4 Nh4 22. Bh1
{ Plan: Re2, Rh2, and attack on the h-file. Don't forget about Ne5, too - the knight might get useful for the attack. }
