{ In the following chapters of 1... Nf6, we will consider 2... c5, 2... e6 and 2... b6. }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 c5 3. Bb2 Nc6 4. e3
{ g3 and Bg2 run in all sorts of issues. For example, Black can try ...d5, ...d4, and ...e5. Breaking that wall of pawns might be a little challenging, to say the least. }
4... e6 5. Be2 d5 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. dxc5
{ Opening up the bishop on b2 and preparing c4. } 8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. a3
{ Aiming for b4. } 10... e5 11. b4 Bd6 12. c4
{ A quick c4 is neccessary; otherwise, they play e4 and Ne5 and don't let us challenge the pawn on d5. }
12... e4 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Re8 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Qc2
{ The plan: Rfd1, Nf1-g3, Rac1. White is better since we control the open files and the pawn on e4 needs constant protection, tying up Black's pieces. }
