{ g3 and Bg2 run in all sorts of issues. For example, Black can try ...d5, ...d4, and ...e5. Breaking that wall of pawns might be a little challenging, to say the least. }
4... e6 5. Be2 d5 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. dxc5
{ Opening up the bishop on b2 and preparing c4. } 8... Bxc5 9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. a3
{ Aiming for b4. } 10... a5 11. c4 Rd8 12. Qc2 d4
{ 12...Ba7  13.Rfd1⩲  The plan: Rac1, Bd3, with the threat of taking on d5 and creating a weak isolate pawn for Black.   12...Bd6  13.Bd3⩲  Our follow up most likely will be Rfe1 with the subsequent e4. }
13. exd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Bxd4
{ Lots of trades but don't despair: we still have one trick up our sleeve! }
15... Rxd4 16. b4 { Here it is! } 16... axb4 17. Qb2
{ A double attack, winning the pawn back and enjoying 2 vs. 1 pawn majority on the queenside. While White's advantage may seem insignificant, we would like to point out that Black still faces challenges on the queenside and that any endgame could be potentially deadly for Black. }
17... Rd8 18. axb4 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 *

