{ You never know if your opponents want to gamble, so let's check this. } 9.
Qxb5
{ We should accept the pawn sacrifice, in the best traditions of the 18th-century style duels. }
9... Nb4 10. a3 Ba6 { 10...Nxc2  11.Ra2+-  wins the knight on c2. } 11. Qa4
{ It's all under control, folks. } 11... Bxf1 12. Bxf1 Nxc2 13. Ra2
{ Now, Black faces a tough challenge: how to save the knight? We believe only an exceptionally gifted player would be able to get away with this as Black. If they do, check if they are using outside help @@StartBracket@@Stockfish 15 might do the trick@@EndBracket@@. }
13... d4 14. Qc4 Qd5 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 16. e4
{ Time to say farewell to the knight? } 16... Rab8
{ If you ever get here, we assume your opponent is at least 2500 FIDE. Taking on d5 isn't worth it - Black would capture the b3 and then d5.   16...Nf6  17.Bd3±  Here is our grand prize! }
17. Bc4 Rfd8 { Another impossible move, keeping Black alive. } 18. Kg2
{ A waiting move. } 18... Nf6 19. d3
{ We like this for White. Black still faces some tough questions and the knight's fate on c2 is hanging on a thin thread. }
