[White "1.4) 1...Nf6 2.b3 e6"]
[Black "3...d5 4.c4 Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 e6 3. Bb2 d5
{ This line may be employed quite frequently by anybody who's a fan of the Queen's Gambit @@StartBracket@@the opening or the TV series, or both!@@EndBracket@@. }
4. c4 { We need to challenge Black before they go c5 and d4. } 4... Be7 5. e3
O-O 6. Nc3 c5 7. cxd5
{ We need to take on d5 and follow up with d2-d4 right away! Otherwise, Black hits us with d4 and destroys White's hopes and dreams... Well, maybe not hopes and dreams but the bishop on b2 for sure. }
7... Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 9. d4
{ One thing we know for sure: allowing Black to play Nb8-c6 and then d5-d4 would have been a major upset for the backbone of this system and the course - the bishop on b2. }
9... Nc6 10. Be2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qa5+
{ If Black doesn't check our king, we simply short castle and play Rc1, Bf3, and have an easy play against the isolani on d5. }
12. Kf1
{ We don't even mind losing castling rights as long as Black gets that isolated pawn on d5. Nakamura keeps exploiting those positions for White very successfully. }
12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bf5 14. Bd3
{ Black's bishop on f5 is too active, so it makes sense to get rid of it before Black uses it effectively to help the rooks to infiltrate the second rank after Rac8 and Rc2. }
14... Be4 15. Bxe4
{ Also possible is  15.f3  Bxd3+  16.Qxd3  Rfe8  17.Kf2⩲  as seen in the game Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Martirosyan, H @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@, 1-0, Chess.com INT 2020. }
15... dxe4 16. Qg4
{ A double attack on e4 and g7, winning one of the pawns. We would hope they miss a checkmate on g7! :@@EndBracket@@ }
16... Bf6 17. Qxe4 Qa6+ 18. Kg1
{ We were following the game Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@ - So,W @@StartBracket@@2754@@EndBracket@@, Abidjan 2019. }
