1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 b6
{ Welcome to the copycat line! Usually employed by the players who like fianchetto, Queen's Indian setups, or lack imagination :@@EndBracket@@ }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. g3 Bxf3
{ An early capture on f3 gives us a lot of options and leaves a gaping hole on the b7. }
5. exf3 e6 6. Bg2 d5
{ Sooner or later, Black needs to take measures against our bishop on g2. } 7.
O-O g6
{ Other moves would make it too easy for us to push f4 and eventually f5 @@StartBracket@@after Qf3, for example@@EndBracket@@, opening up the e-file and weakening the pawn on d5. Our bishop on g2 would also improve dramatically if the f4-f5 idea came to fruition. }
8. f4 Bg7 9. c4 O-O 10. d4
{ The only sensible placement here. We don't like going d3 since it allows Black to move the knight on f6 and trade the bishops. }
10... Nc6 11. Nd2
{ We have seen this maneuver in the previous chapters. The plan: Nf3-e5, Qe2, Rad1, h4, Bf3, h5. }
