{ 4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  b6  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 d5 8. cxd5
{ We need to define Black's plans. Ideally, we would like them to take with the pawn and go to a favorable Queen's Indian-type position. }
8... Nxd5 9. d4 c5 { Without c5, Black has too little space. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5
11. Nbd2
{ We have a small but stable advantage due to a double fiancetto and more agile knights. }
11... Nd7 12. Nc4 Qe7 13. e4
{ The pawn goes to e5 and makes our bid for the d6 control much stronger. }
13... N5f6 14. e5 Nd5 15. Qe2 a5 16. a4
{ Stopping Black from causing any damage to our queenside with a4. } 16... Rfd8
17. Rfd1 Rac8 18. h4
{ As seen in the game Svidler, P @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Eljanov, P @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@, chess.com INT 2020. The plan: Ng5-e4-d6! We could also aim for h5-h6 later. }
