{ 4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  b6  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 d5 8. cxd5
{ We need to define Black's plans. Ideally, we would like them to take with the pawn and go to a favorable Queen's Indian-type position. }
8... Bxd5 9. Nc3 { Gaining a tempo and developing a knight. } 9... Bb7 10. d4
c5 11. dxc5
{ Swedish Grandmaster Ulf Andersson used to be an expert in playing symmetrical positions with a double fiancetto @@StartBracket@@or just with the bishop on g2@@EndBracket@@. We recommend looking up his games and learning how he did his magic. }
11... Bxc5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Rfd1
{ We are a little ahead in development and will be trading the light-squared bishops soon. }
13... Nbd7 14. Nd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Rac8 16. Rac1
{ Black's pawn structure on the queenside remains vulnerable due to a weakness of the c6 square and easy access to the b5-square. Notice that Black would have no issues if their pawns were on a6 and b7. Such a small detail but look how much it changes everything! }
16... a6 17. Na4
{ Black can't move the bishop back because of Nc6. Our plan: a3, b4, and pressure Black on the queenside. }
