3. Bb2 Bb7 4. g3 e6
{ 4...g6  5.Bg2  Bg7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  b6  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 c5 8. d4 cxd4
{ 8...d5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Nbd2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nf6  2.b3  b6  3.Bb2  Bb7  4.g3  e6  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  d5  8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.d4  c5  10.dxc5  Bxc5  11.Nbd2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qf4 { The best square for the queen. } 10... d5 11. Rd1
{ We need to anticipate well in advance which files can be opened in the middle game. With a high degree of certainty, we are betting on d- and c-files, hence the rooks should go on d1 and c1. }
11... Qc8 12. Nc3
{ We need to finish our queenside development and bring the rook from a1 to c1 in the future. }
12... dxc4 13. Qxc4
{ The only recapture that makes sense. Taking with the b3 pawn would only create a weak isolani on c4, and Black could have exploited it with moves like Na5. }
13... Nb4 14. Ne5
{ Trading the light square bishops helps us gain more control over Black's queenside and potentially establish an outpost for the knight on c6. }
14... Bxg2 15. Qxc8 Raxc8 16. Kxg2
{ White is a tiny bit better and has absolutely no risk of losing. The plan: Rac1, a3, b4, Nb5. The money square: c6. If you get your knight there, you should have no issues winning the game. }
