[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to Part Two"]
[Black "Introduction to Part Two"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5
{ Part Two will examine Black's setups with 1... d5. It's the second most common move, closely trailing 1... Nf6. You may see 1...d5 played most frequently by someone who aims for the openings such as Queen's Gambit, Slav Defense, or simply enjoys getting the bishop out of c8 as quickly as possible. }
2. b3 Bf5
{ A solid approach, immediately taking care of the queenside development. We should note that the light-squared bishop is a usual cause for pain for Black if they first move e7-e6, thus locking the bishop on c8 for an extended period of time.   •  2...Bg4  One of the most active systems for Black. As compared to 1...d5 2.b3 Bf5, the bishop can't be attacked with e4 later in the opening.  3.Bb2  Bxf3   3...Nd7  4.g3  Covered as the main line in chapter 2.1  4.exf3  The goal is to build a fortress for the king after a short castle: f2-f4-g3-h2. Chapter 2.1 will show you how reliable and exciting this pawn structure is for White.   •  2...Nf6  3.Bb2  c5  4.e3  Playing g3 would not be recommended since Black can immediately lock up our bishop on b2 for a long time: d5-d4 and Nb8-c6.  4...g6   4...Nc6  5.Bb5  transposes to chapter 2.3.  5.c4  We challenge Black in the center immediately and will take on d5 right away. The resulting pawn structures are better for White as we show in chapter 2.2.   •  2...c5  3.e3!  The only move! We can't play Bc1-b2 since Black gains control of the center right away after 3... f7-f6, followed by 4...  e7-e5.  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  Nf6  5.Bb5  While the bishop isn't in the usual position on g2, it still does a good job tormenting Black's position. Black pretty much has to play Bd7 or otherwise face the consequences of a damaged pawn structure after Bb5-c6. We will follow up with a short castle and d2-d4, as shown in chapter 2.3.   •  2...Nc6  Typically, Black should move the pawn to c5 and then go Nb8-c6. The knight on c6 blocks its own pawn on c7, hence Black's pressure on the White's center is far less profound.  3.Bb2  Bg4  4.e3  You may have noticed that we prefer e2-e3 whenever Black's knights appear on c6 since we can pin it nicely after Bf1-b5. Chapter 2.4 will feature some of the major plans for White, including going for the exciting long castle in one of the lines. }
3. Bb2 e6 4. g3
{ For the most part, we should develop the bishop on g2 in the majority of cases. The exception could be the lines where Black plays 1... d5 and 2... c5, where we prefer an early 3. e3 and potential Bb5. }
4... Nf6 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. d3
{ Whenever you see the bishop on f5, play d3. White's plan is to limit the bishop on f5, play Nbd2 and get e2-e4 going at some point. Chapter 2 will uncover the most relevant moves you need to remember to succeed against this setup. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1) 1...d5 2.b3 Bf5"]
[Black "3...Nf6 4.g3 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ After exploring  1...Nf6  in the first part, we will move on to the next most common move, 1... d5. The second part will have plenty of chapters, which will cover Black's setups with various moves on move 2: ...Bf5, ...Bg4, ...Nf6, ...c5, and ...Nc6. }
1... d5 2. b3 Bf5 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. g3 c5
{ A tricky move order.  4...e6  5.Bg2  transposes to the mainline. } 5. Bg2 Nc6
{ Luckily for us, this setup is exceptionally rare. The authors were going back and forth on this one, finally settling on a rather unconventional approach. }
6. d3
{ Nothing strange here yet. We are used to seeing the pawn on d3, especially if it means limiting the bishop on f5. }
6... Qc7 7. Qd2
{ There we go! This one will need some deciphering on our end. So: 1@@EndBracket@@ we know that Black aims for e5; 2@@EndBracket@@ we are ready to meet it with Qg5. }
7... e5 8. Qg5 { Wins the pawn. } 8... Be6 9. Bxe5
{ It's important to understand why Ne5 doesn't work, so please take time to click through some of the variations there.   9.Nxe5??  h6  The issue is that the knight on e5 turns out to be a very fragile piece.  10.Qf4   10.Qe3  d4  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  12.Qf3  Bd5!  Black can't take on e5 because of Qc6.  13.Qf5  Bxh1  14.f3-+  Down a rook is not exactly a definition of a good start.  10...Bd6  11.O-O  Bxe5  12.Bxe5  Qxe5  13.Qxe5  Nxe5  14.Nc3-+  The only way for White to save this is to receive a lot of help from Black. And we mean like a loooooot of help. }
9... Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Bd6 11. Qb2
{ A cozy spot for the queen and a healthy extra pawn for us. We need to castle short, play Nd2, e3, d4. }
