1... d5 2. b3 Bf5 3. Bb2 e6
{ 3...Nd7  4.d3  Ngf6  5.Nbd2  e6  6.g3  Be7  7.Bg2  O-O  8.O-O  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/8/1P3N2/PBPPPPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.g3  Nf6  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.d3  Nbd7  8.Nbd2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   3...f6  makes no sense because of  4.d4  and the pawn on f6 turns out to be punishing its own friendly knight on g8 while contributing nothing to the game. }
4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Bd6
{ The bishop on d6 is misplaced. Black will need to move it back to e7 and lose a valuable tempo once we launch e4. }
6. d3 O-O 7. Nbd2 h6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Re1 { Preparing e4. } 9... Bh7 10. e4 dxe4
{ Can't be recommended for Black as we now get a perfect square on c4 for the knight. }
11. dxe4 e5 12. Nc4 Qe7 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Nd2 { An attempt to transfer to c4. }
14... b5 15. Nf1
{ Since c4 is unavailable, we pick another route for our knight. } 15... a5 16.
f3 a4 17. Ne3
{ White is significantly better due to a bishop pair, d6 weakness, and out-of-play bishop on h7. }
