{ 3...Nd7  4.d3  Ngf6  5.Nbd2  e6  6.g3  Be7  7.Bg2  O-O  8.O-O  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p1b2/8/1P3N2/PBPPPPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...e6  4.g3  Nf6  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.d3  Nbd7  8.Nbd2  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   3...f6  makes no sense because of  4.d4  and the pawn on f6 turns out to be punishing its own friendly knight on g8 while contributing nothing to the game. }
4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6
{ Resembles 3... c5 line. However, there is one key difference: Black has already played e6, so ideas like Qc7 and then e5 lose their appeal @@StartBracket@@why waste a tempo with e6 then?@@EndBracket@@. }
7. d3 Be7
{ 7...Bd6  The bishop here gets hit with e4-e5.  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.Re1⩲  e2-e4 is coming. }
8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Ne5
{ White's plan here is to trade the minor pieces and start attacking Black's queenside, restricting the light-squared bishop. Truly, with the pawn being on d3 and us attacking with c4 later, the bishop looks completely lost on f5. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Nd7 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Qc1
{ A standard idea. The queen on b2 is incredibly useful. } 12... Bxb2 13. Qxb2
Nf6 14. c4
{ The plan: attack the queenside with Rfc1, Rab1, a3, b4. A pawn trade on d5 can be strongly considered as well. }
