{ One of the most active systems for Black. As compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  Bf5  ,  the bishop can't be attacked with e4 later in the opening. }
3. Bb2 Nd7
{ The mainline. Black will now continue with ...Ngf6, ...e6 followed by ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
4. g3 Ngf6 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Be7
{ A lot less challenging than 6...Bd6 since Black doesn't have e5. } 7. d3 O-O
8. Nbd2 c6 9. h3
{ We get the feeling h3 is played almost in 100% of the cases when the bishop is on g4. }
9... Bxf3 10. Nxf3 a5 11. a3
{ Getting ready to meet a4 with b4, another typical idea to remember. } 11...
a4 12. b4 c5 13. bxc5 Nxc5 14. Rb1
{ The rook on b1 is a common feature whenever the b-file is open. White's plan is Nd2 and c4, followed by a pawn trade cxd5. }
