3. Bb2 Nd7
{ The mainline. Black will now continue with ...Ngf6, ...e6 followed by ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
4. g3 Ngf6 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Be7
{ A lot less challenging than 6...Bd6 since Black doesn't have e5. } 7. d3 O-O
8. Nbd2 c6 9. h3
{ We get the feeling h3 is played almost in 100% of the cases when the bishop is on g4. }
9... Bh5 10. g4
{ White takes advantage of the fact that Black hasn't played h7-h6. } 10... Bg6
11. Nh4 { Bishop pair advantage! } 11... Ne8 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. e3
{ Notice that we have too many pawns on the light squares, so it wouldn't hurt to cover up the dark squares as well. If you have too many pawns on the light squares, your dark squares may get painfully weak. }
13... Nd6 14. c4 Bf6 15. d4
{ White is better due to a bishop pair and advantage in space. } *

