1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bg4
{ One of the most active systems for Black. As compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  Bf5  ,  the bishop can't be attacked with e4 later in the opening. }
3. Bb2 Nd7
{ The mainline. Black will now continue with ...Ngf6, ...e6 followed by ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
4. g3 Ngf6 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 8. d4
{ Whenever the bishop is on g4 --> Put the pawn on d4 and try to occupy the e5 square with the knight on f3. }
8... O-O 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Nd2 Bxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. Nf3
{ The pawn on e5 needs protection. } 12... Be4 13. h3
{ We need to resolve the issues with Black's unwelcomed activity and push back the intruders as quickly as we can. In a process, we sacrifice the pawn on e5. }
13... Bxf3
{ 13...Nh6  14.g4±  Prevents Nf5 and keeps the knight out of play for a long time. The plan: Qd2, Rac1, Qe3, Rfd1. Attack on the queenside. }
14. exf3 Ngxe5 15. f4 Ng6 16. f5
{ A pawn sacrifice is a natural way to open up the position for your monster bishops. }
16... exf5 { 16...Ne7  17.fxe6  fxe6  18.Re1±  wins the pawn back. } 17. cxd5
cxd5 18. Qxd5
{ The plan: bring the rooks to d1 and e1 and obliterate Black's queenside. } *

