1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bg4
{ One of the most active systems for Black. As compared to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  Bf5  ,  the bishop can't be attacked with e4 later in the opening. }
3. Bb2 Nd7
{ The mainline. Black will now continue with ...Ngf6, ...e6 followed by ...c6 and ...Bd6. }
4. g3 Ngf6 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Bd6 7. c4 c6 8. d4
{ Whenever the bishop is on g4 --> Put the pawn on d4 and try to occupy the e5 square with the knight on f3. }
8... O-O 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Nd2 h6 11. e3
{ The pawn is always useful on e3: supports d4, prepares Qe2, and could support f4 as well. }
11... Qc7 12. Ndf3 { The plan: Rc1-Qe2-Rfd1. } 12... Ne4 13. Rc1 Ndf6 14. Ne1
{ The key move whenever the Black's knight gets to e4 - we must not tolerate it's activity and kick it out with f3! }
14... Nd7 15. f3 Nef6 16. cxd5 exd5 17. e4
{ Never miss a chance to play e4, especially if it comes with a nice tactical surprise. }
17... dxe4 18. fxe4 Bxe4 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Rxf6
{ The key idea behind the pawn sacrifice on the 17th move. } 20... Bxg2 21.
Rxd6 Qxd6 22. Nxg2
{ White has a slightly better game. Our plan for improvement could be Qf3, Rf1, Ne3 with the idea of getting the knight to f5 and, potentially, attacking the king. }
