{ 10...Qc7  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.f3  is the same as @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1n1ppp/2pbpn2/3pNb2/2PP4/1P4P1/PB1NPPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qe7  11.Nxd7  Qxd7  12.f3  . }
11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. f3
{ Quite often, aiming for e4 and space control is the only sensible idea. }
12... Bg6 13. e4 dxe4 14. fxe4 e5
{ Otherwise, Black is strategically lost.  14...Bh5  is a senseless move that we can use to illustrate the necessity of 14...e5  15.Qc2  Bg6  16.c5  preparing Nc4.  16...Bc7  17.Nc4± }
15. Nf3 Nxe4
{ This move starts a series of exchanges that simplify the position in White's favor. }
16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Rad8 18. Qxd7 Rxd7 19. Rfe1 Ng5 20. Rad1 Rfd8 21. Rd6
{ As seen in the game Romanovsky,P-Botvinnik,M, Leningrad 1931. Plan: Get the other rook to d1, facilitate the rook trades, and, ideally win the endgame with 2 bishops vs. knight + bishop. }
