1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 g6 4. c4 c6
{ 4...dxc4  5.bxc4  Bg7  6.g3  c5  7.Bg2  O-O  8.O-O  Nc6  9.d3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  O-O  5.Bg2  d5  6.c4  dxc4  7.bxc4  c5  8.O-O  Nc6  9.d3  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
5. e3
{ Sometimes, it makes sense to develop the bishop to e2. Here, Black has already committed to d5-c6 structure, so we know in advance our bishop wouldn't be the most effective on g2. In some other chapters @@StartBracket@@like 1... d5 2. b3 Bg4 or 2... Bf5@@EndBracket@@ we still develop our bishop to g2 and compensate for that with a prompt attack of the h1-a8 diagonal. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. d3
{ The only sensible square. Putting the pawn on d4 would allow Ne4. } 8... Nbd7
9. Nbd2 Re8 10. h3 { We need to get a bishop pair advantage. } 10... Bxf3 11.
Nxf3 e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Rc1
{ We saw a very similar position in 1... Nf6 2. b3 g6 chapter. The plan: a3, b4, and then Qb3. Alternatively, we could also go a3-b4, Rc2, Qa1, Rfc1. It all depends on your personal preferences, taste, and your opponent's moves, of course. }
*

