4. e3 Bg4 { Not as good as it looks. } 5. h3
{ It's smart to attack the bishop as soon as possible and have some more clarity about Black's intentions. }
5... Bh5 { gives White a solid edge. } 6. g4
{ Emphasizes why moving the bishop out so early wasn't the best idea. } 6...
Bg6 7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight and getting ready to ruin Black's pawn structure on the queenside. }
8... Qc7 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. d3
{ d3 only! Placing pawn on d4 would fix Black's pawn structure and open up the bishop on g6. }
10... e6 11. Nd2
{ One of the authors coaches a 7-year prodigy from New York, who regularly gets this particular position with slight deviations and already knows the best plans: f4-Qe2 and then O-O-O! We may advance our f, g, and h-pawns as far we like, further putting Black under pressure. The key idea to remember: whenever Black goes a7-a5, we should respond with a2-a4, blocking any counterattack on the queenside. }
