{ The only move!  3.Bb2?!  doesn't work because of  3...f6!  and nothing can prevent Black from going ...e5 the next move. }
3... Nc6
{ •  3...f6  4.d4!  cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.Bb2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  f6  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   •  3...a6  4.Bb2  Nc6  5.d4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  a6  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Bb2 Bf5 5. Bb5 Rc8
{ Naturally, Black doesn't want to fight an uphill battle with the damaged pawn structure after Bc6, so the rook is ready to recapture on c6. }
6. O-O a6 7. Bxc6+ Rxc6 8. c4
{ We need to hit Black's center before they catch up in development. } 8... e6
{ 8...dxc4  fails rather quickly due to  9.Ne5  Rc8  10.Qf3+- } 9. cxd5 exd5
10. d4 { Ready to take on c5. } 10... Nf6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Nd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4
O-O 14. Nc3
{ The plan: pressure the pawn on d5 and connect the rooks like Rac1 and Rfd1. Avoid trading the minor pieces since our bishop and knight are vastly superior. Knight can go to e2 and then f4. }
*

