3... Nc6
{ •  3...f6  4.d4!  cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.Bb2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  f6  5.d4  cxd4  6.exd4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@.   •  3...a6  4.Bb2  Nc6  5.d4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  4.Bb2  a6  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Bb2 f6 5. d4 { Whenever they want to put 3 pawns on the 5th rank, play d4! }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Bg4 7. Nbd2 e5 8. dxe5 fxe5 9. Be2
{ The position is wide open, so we need to short castle soon. This move also creates a threat of Ne5. }
9... e4
{ 9...Bxf3  10.Bxf3  Nf6  11.c4!±  Black's center is about to crumble. } 10.
Ne5 Bxe2 11. Qxe2
{ The plan: O-O-O and attack the center. When we played 9. Be2, short castle was the only available @@StartBracket@@and the fastest@@EndBracket@@ option. Now, we can pick and choose, so we have decided that the newly available long castle will add more spice to the game than a short castle. As a general rule, if your opponent's king is stuck in the middle, the long castle is the best way to exploit it since it brings the rook to d1 and attacks the king right away. }
