[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5) 1...d5 2.b3 Nc6"]
[Black "3...Bf5 4.e3 e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Nc6 { The knight is ready to support the e5-advance. } 3. Bb2
Bf5 4. e3 e6 5. Bb5 { Allowing Bb5 brings a major headache for Black } 5... Ne7
6. O-O a6 7. Be2
{ We don't want to take on c6 as it would improve Black's knight on e7. } 7...
Bg6 8. d4 Nf5 9. c4 { Gaining a sizeable amount of center. } 9... Be7 10. Nc3
O-O 11. Rc1
{ White's plan is to expand on the queenside after a3 and b4, followed by Qb3 @@StartBracket@@threatens to win the pawn on d5@@EndBracket@@. It will force Black to trade the pawns on c4, which will give us a bigger center - 2 pawns on e3 and d4 vs. one pawn on e6 - and, hence, more space. Once the trade on c4 is complete @@StartBracket@@we take with the bishop@@EndBracket@@, we might follow up with Rfd1 and d5, unleashing the power of the bishops on c4 and b2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.5) 1...d5 2.b3 Nc6"]
[Black "3...Bf5 4.e3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Nc6 { The knight is ready to support the e5-advance. } 3. Bb2
Bf5 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bb5 Bd7
{ 5...a6  leads to a terrible pawn structure for Black.  6.Bxc6+  bxc6  7.d3  e6  8.Nbd2± }
6. O-O e6 7. d4 Bd6 8. Bd3
{ The bishop is done on b5 and it's time to relocate. } 8... O-O 9. a3
{ Stopping Nb4 and preparing c4. } 9... Ne4 10. c4 f5 11. Nc3
{ The knight on e4 and the stonewall structure isn't as dangerous as it looks. }
11... Be8 12. c5 { Removing the bishop from its sweet spot on d6. } 12... Be7
13. b4 Bf6
{ 13...Bh5  14.Ne2!±  If Black takes on f3, we would force the knight on e4 to go back. Then, we would play Kh1, Rg1, and attack on the g-file. Our knight will still go to f4. }
14. Ne2 b6 15. Nf4
{ White's progress is apparent across the board, especially on the queenside. We could further improve by targeting the knight on e4 with Nd2 and then f3. It also wouldn't hurt to bring the rook from a1 to c1, and consider Qb3-Rc2-Rfc1 in the future. }
*

