1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Nc6 { The knight is ready to support the e5-advance. } 3. Bb2
Bg4 { Pinning the knight and, again, playing for ...e5. } 4. e3 a6 5. h3
{ Pushing the bishop away before it gets too comfortable on g4. } 5... Bh5 6.
Be2 e6 7. O-O Nf6 8. d3
{ It's rather a temporary measure. We need to bring the knight in, and only then play d4 here. The reason: if we go d4 too soon, Black brings the knight to e4 and goes f5. White is better off by waiting a bit and then expanding. }
8... Bd6 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. c4 a5 11. a3 { A typical idea, preparing against a4. }
11... Re8 12. d4
{ The expansion on the queenside is the name of the game: Black's life may become unbearably tough after we play Rc1, c5, Bc3, and b4. }
