[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to Part Three"]
[Black "Introduction to Part Three"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3
{ We wouldn't recommend going 2. e4 unless you are comfortable with the countless lines in the Sicilians that require precise memorization quite often until move 20 and beyond. This course is all about utility - our goal is to provide an interesting opening repertoire that maximizes the ratio between the time you put into studying and the outcomes.   The best part about this 1. Nf3 course is that you don't have to worry about forgetting the lines since just knowing the first few moves and the general ideas will suffice for being successful. }
2... d6
{ Black, of course, has some other move like ...Nc6, ...Nf6, ...d5 etc. They usually transpose to the lines we have already considered in Part 1 and Part 2. }
3. c4
{ Other moves don't look as promising to us. Part 3 will expose some of the interesting ideas in a pure English Opening - it's when we put the pawn on c4 and Black eventually responds with ...e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 1...c5"]
[Black "2...Nc6 3.Bb2 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3
