1. Nf3 c5 2. b3
{ After boldly landing your knight on f3, you may face 1... c5 if you face anybody who would ordinarily play Sicilian Defense vs. 1. e4. We would not advise going 2. e4 in this instance since it will open up a completely new can of worms - about 12495837 lines of Sicilian Defense. Okay, we have to admit that the number is completely made up.   However, you get the point - you wouldn't want to memorize countless Sicilians and we wouldn't want to write about them @@StartBracket@@not until the next year at least!@@EndBracket@@. Instead, move your pawn to b3! This chapter will expose some of the interesting ideas in a pure English Opening - it's when we put the pawn on c4 and Black eventually responds with e5. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb2 e6 4. e4 { One of the very few cases when e4 is possible. }
4... d5 5. Bb5 Nf6 6. exd5 exd5 7. Qe2+ Qe7
{ 7...Be7  8.Bxf6  Decisively ruins Black's pawn structure on the kingside.  8...gxf6  9.O-O⩲ }
8. Ne5 Bd7 9. Bxc6
{ The move order matters here. If we took with the knight first, Black can recapture with the pawn on b7, forcing our bishop to leave. }
9... Bxc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxf6
{ Creating even more pawn weaknesses for Black. } 11... gxf6 12. Nc3
{ White has a solid edge due to multiple double pawns in Black's position. We would be happy to trade the queens since the better pawn structures are more advantageous when the attack on our king is eliminated completely. If Black trades the queens now, we take with the king, move it to f3 next, and then proceed with Ne2-g3-f5. }
