Nc3 e6
{ 4...Nc6  5.d4  cxd4  6.Nxd4  e6  7.Bb2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pb1ppppp/1p6/2p5/4P3/1PN2N2/P1PP1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...e6  5.Bb2  Nc6  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Bb2 Nc6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Bd3 Bb4 10. O-O Qb8
{ A tough move to find over the board. The queen stops e5 and also avoids getting hit with Nc3-b5.   10...Qc7  11.Nb5!?  we would like to claim the bishop pair advantage.   11.Qe2  is also not so bad.  11...Bxb5  12.Bxb5⩲ }
11. Qe2 { Insisting on pushing e5 on the next move. } 11... Bd6 12. h3
{ Dropping the pawn on h2 is definitely not recommended. } 12... Be5
{ Black may wish to challenge our bishop on b2 and stop e5 for a while. } 13.
Rae1
{ We would like to connect all of our pieces and reinforces the threat of e5 in the future. }
13... O-O 14. a4
{ This move stops Black from playing b5 and expanding on the queenside. In turn, our plan could include Nd1, bishop trade, and subsequent attack on the kingside with f4 and e5. }
*

