{ •  2...d5  3.e3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d5  2.b3  c5  3.e3  @@StartBracket@@see the chapter@@EndBracket@@.   •  2...Nf6  3.Bb2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Nf6  2.b3  c5  3.Bb2  @@StartBracket@@see the chapter@@EndBracket@@. }
3. c4
{ Other moves don't look as promising to us. The central pawn configuration can be quite different in this section of the course compared to others. }
3... e5 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. g3 g6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O
{ No need to play Bb2 just yet as it's too early to tell if we need the bishop there or not. }
7... Nge7 8. Bb2
{ Unlike with the Black's knight on f6, we won't be able to trade the bishop, so we simply develop it to b2. }
8... O-O 9. d3 f5 10. a3 f4
{ 10...h6  11.Nd2  transposes to @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2npbp/2np2p1/2p1p3/2P5/1PNP1NP1/PB2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...h6  10.Nd2  f5  11.a3  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Rb1 h6 12. b4 { A pawn sacrifice is neccessary to break on the queenside. }
12... cxb4 13. axb4 Nxb4 14. Ba3 { The bishop is finally truly in the game. }
14... Nbc6 15. Ne4 Nf5 16. g4
{ Even the g-pawn participates in our queenside endeavors! } 16... Nh4 17. Nxh4
Qxh4 18. Nxd6 { We take a plunge into some wild complications. } 18... Bxg4 19.
Rxb7 Nd4 20. Bd5+ Kh7 21. f3
{ White is winning according to the engine. We still need to do a lot of work to make it a reality. }
21... Bh3 22. Ne4
{ The only move! Apparently, the bishop on h3 is worth more than the rook on f1. After  22...Bxf1  23.Qxf1  Rfe8  24.Qf2±  White's ideas are Bd6, attacking the e5-pawn, Bf7, attacking the g6-pawn, and the pawn advance c5-c6. }
