2... Bg7 3. d4 d6
{ 3...c5  4.dxc5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  c5  3.d4  Bg7  4.dxc5  which is covered in chapter 4.2. }
4. Bc4
{ The most natural development, employing the bishop on the most dangerous a2-g8 diagonal and eyeing the f7 pawn. }
4... Nf6 5. Qe2
{ Another crucial move to remember. The queen will support our e4 pawn nicely and might help with a typical e4-e5 pawn break in the center. }
5... Nc6 6. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4 is usually a great idea. } 6... O-O 7. O-O e5
8. dxe5
{ The only sensible approach. Playing d5 would obliterate our bishop on c4, and letting Black take on d4 would endanger the stability of our center. }
8... Nxe5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. Kh2
{ Prophylaxis! The king is going to help with g3, thus stopping the Black's knight from infiltrating our camp via h5 and then f4. }
11... Nh5 12. g3
{ Stopping Nf4. The plan: Nc3, Be3, a4, a5 and aim for a qeenside attack. } *

