[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2) 1...g6 2.e4 c5 3.d4 Bg7"]
[Black "4...Na6 5.Bxa6 bxa6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 c5
{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense @@StartBracket@@this chapter, 4.2@@EndBracket@@ or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation @@StartBracket@@the next chapter, 4.3@@EndBracket@@. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until a few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 Bg7 4. dxc5 Na6
{ Bizzare knight development, quite frankly. No wonder, White achieves a huge advantage in every single line. }
5. Bxa6 bxa6 { This is utterly ugly. } 6. Qd5 Rb8 7. Ne5
{ Hitting the f7 pawn and threatening to checkmate in 1. It's worth noting White needs to play fast and provoke as many weaknesses as possible before Black wakes up and finally catches up in development. }
7... e6
{ Taking the knight on e5 with the bishop on g7 wasn't an option as both Black rooks on b8 and h8 would be under attack after Qxe5:  7...Bxe5  8.Qxe5 }
8. Qd6 Rb4 9. O-O
{ Terrible pawn structure? Check. Behind in development? Check. Can't take the e4 pawn because of tactics? Check. Conclusion: White is winning. }
9... Bf8 { doesn't fare much better than the rook's capture on e4 } 10. Qd3 f6
{ 10...Bxc5  11.Qc3+-  X-ray on the a1-h8 diagonal, in addition to a double attack on the rook and bishop, makes this an easily winnable game for White. }
11. Nc4 Bxc5 12. Bd2
{ Attacking the most active piece and effectively developing our bishop. }
12... Rb8 13. Ba5
{ Continuing the trend - the best development is always accompanied with the attack on your opponent's pieces. }
13... Bb6 14. Qg3
{ Hitting the rook on b8, forcing it to return to a8, and thus causing even more damage to Black's development. }
14... Ra8 15. Nd6+ Kf8 16. Bc3 { White's dominance is undeniable. } *

