1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 c5
{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense @@StartBracket@@this chapter, 4.2@@EndBracket@@ or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation @@StartBracket@@the next chapter, 4.3@@EndBracket@@. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until a few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 Bg7 4. dxc5 Na6
{ Bizzare knight development, quite frankly. No wonder, White achieves a huge advantage in every single line. }
5. Bxa6 Qa5+ 6. Bd2 Qxa6 7. Nc3 Qc6
{ Strikes us as odd to move the queen around so much... You still need to see how to react to this move, as we assume that many people may be enticed by the pawn on c5. }
8. Nd5
{ The best spot for the knight! It comes at as small price though: we need to sacrifice our pawn on b2. }
8... Qxc5 9. O-O d6
{ Before getting the knight out from g8 to f6, Black needs to make sure the e7 pawn is protected in case on Bb4. }
10. Bb4 Qc6 11. Nd4 { Relentless pressure is the name of the game! } 11... Bxd4
12. Qxd4 f6 13. c4
{ Black is far behind in development and unlikely to withstand an upcoming pawn, amplified by the rooks like this: f4, e5, Rae1. }
