{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense @@StartBracket@@this chapter, 4.2@@EndBracket@@ or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation @@StartBracket@@the next chapter, 4.3@@EndBracket@@. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until a few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 Bg7 4. dxc5 Nf6
{ Not a frequent move, but worthwile considering since it looks quite logical. }
5. Nc3 Qa5 6. e5
{ Our e4-pawn got attacked on the previous move @@StartBracket@@the knight on c3 got pinned, thus enabling Nf6-e4@@EndBracket@@, so it makes sense to make a target an attacker. }
6... Ne4 7. Qd4 Nxc3 8. Bd2
{ Delayed capture! After playing this game for over 40 years between the two of the authors, we can safely say that the perfect case scenario in chess is attack, attack, and only then capture. The same stands true for defense: attack, attack, and only then retreat. }
8... Nc6 9. Qxc3 Qc7 10. Bf4
{ Saving the pawn and cementing our domination in the center. } 10... O-O 11.
O-O-O
{ You would need a miscroscope to see any of Black's compensation for a pawn. Our plan is to push h4 and attack the king. It wouldn't hurt to place the king on b1 - a standard defensive idea to keep thing safer on the queenside. }
