1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 c5
{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense @@StartBracket@@this chapter, 4.2@@EndBracket@@ or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation @@StartBracket@@the next chapter, 4.3@@EndBracket@@. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until a few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 Bg7 4. dxc5 Qc7
{ An attempt to recapture the pawn, just like Qa5. The difference - it doesn't allow us to play Bd2. }
5. c4
{ Choosing a Maroczy bind setup here seems to make a lot of sense. We will try to gain a spacial advantage and put a tight grip on Black's ability to challenge us in the center with the pawn moves like d5 or b5. }
5... Qxc5 6. Be2 Qb4+ 7. Nc3
{ A typical pawn sacrifice. The thesis: Black will face a permanent weakness of the dark squares and won't be able to protect the king adequately. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qxc3+ 9. Bd2 Qa3 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qc2
{ Preparing Bc3 and connecting the rooks } 11... Nf6 12. e5
{ Gaining some more space and attacking the knight, a double win! } 12... Ng4
13. Bc3 O-O 14. h3 Nh6 15. Rab1
{ The plan: Ng5, f4, Bd3, g4, and attack the king. } *

