1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 c5
{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense @@StartBracket@@this chapter, 4.2@@EndBracket@@ or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation @@StartBracket@@the next chapter, 4.3@@EndBracket@@. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until a few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 cxd4
{ Time to learn some Sicilian! We don't want you to worry though. The only Sicilian you would need to learn is Accelerated Dragon. We strongly advocate for an early queen development 4. Qxd4! In many situations, White ends up getting a bishop pair advantage and a comfortable game without any visible weaknesses. }
4. Qxd4
{ This particular line of Sicilian is so bad for Black that would have been a crime not to attempt to punish it! }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Qa4 Bg7 { Allows e5 and thus can't be recommended. } 7.
e5 Ng8 { 7...Nh5?  8.g4+-  Traps the knight and wins the game. } 8. Bf4 f6
{ Otherwise, Black is running out of any reasonable moves. No relief for Black after  8...Nh6  9.h3  O-O  10.O-O-O+-  White's position is technically already winning. Even though we are not up in material, our spacial advantage is absolutely overwhelming. }
9. exf6 Nxf6 10. O-O-O
{ We would always castle long if we could. It's so much fun! } 10... O-O 11.
Bc4+ Kh8 12. Rhe1
{ White's pieces look completely symmetrical. One of the ideas might be going Ng5 if Black decides to play d7-d6 or any other move than Qa5. }
12... d6 { This allows Ng5, which leads to a winning game for White. } 13. Ng5
Ng4
{ 13...Bd7  14.Nf7+  Rxf7  15.Bxf7+-  White's material advantage should be enough for a win. }
14. Nf7+ Rxf7 15. Bxf7 Nxf2 16. Rxd6 { The quickest way to win. } 16... Qf8
{ 16...exd6  17.Re8++- } 17. Qc4
{ We still have Re8 in case they capture our rook, so Black is lost. } *

