4. Qxd4
{ This particular line of Sicilian is so bad for Black that would have been a crime not to attempt to punish it! }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Qa4 d6 7. e5
{ This break in the center improves our knight and damages Black's pawn structure. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bg7 { A popular alternative to the main move. } 9. Nxc6 bxc6
10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qa6 O-O 12. Be2
{ After spending so much time winning a pawn, we must consolidate and bring our king to safety by castling. }
12... Qc7 13. h3
{ A deep move, stopping ...Ng4 in advance.  13.O-O  Ng4  14.Bxg4  Bxg4  With a bishop pair in such an open position, Black has nothing to worry about.  15.Rb1= }
13... Rab8 14. O-O Bf5
{ 14...Bc6  15.Rd1  e6  16.Bf1⩲  We have successfully stabilized our advantage and are ready to expand on the queenside after a4 and Nb5. }
15. Bf3
{ Saving the pawn on c2 would ruin our pawn structure.  15.Bd3  Rb6  Pushes our queen onto the outskirts of the board.  16.Qa3  Bxd3  17.cxd3  Qb7  Black's pressure on b2 and on d3 @@StartBracket@@after Rfd8@@EndBracket@@ is sufficient for achieving an equal play. }
15... Bxc2 16. Re1 e5
{ 16...e6  17.Qe2!  Bf5  18.g4!+-  Suddenly, the bishop is trapped! } 17. Bd1
Bf5 18. Be3 { A temporary pawn sacrifice. } 18... Rxb2 19. Rc1 Qb7
{ Running away from Na4, Nd5, Ne4 and all sorts of threats on the c-file. } 20.
Qa3 Be6 21. Bb3 { Bye-bye, rook! } *

