1. Nf3 g6 2. e4 c5
{ A popular move, leading either to some rare version of Pirc/Modern Defense @@StartBracket@@this chapter, 4.2@@EndBracket@@ or to Sicilian Defense, Accelerated Dragon variation @@StartBracket@@the next chapter, 4.3@@EndBracket@@. Such is the nature of chess openings - you never know what you get until a few moves into the game. White has a variety of decent options here. We will take a close look at one of the most promising ones, the early queen development on move 4. }
3. d4 cxd4
{ Time to learn some Sicilian! We don't want you to worry though. The only Sicilian you would need to learn is Accelerated Dragon. We strongly advocate for an early queen development 4. Qxd4! In many situations, White ends up getting a bishop pair advantage and a comfortable game without any visible weaknesses. }
4. Qxd4
{ This particular line of Sicilian is so bad for Black that would have been a crime not to attempt to punish it! }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Qa4 d6 7. e5
{ This break in the center improves our knight and damages Black's pawn structure. }
7... dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bd7 { 8...Qc7??  A silly blunder.  9.Bf4!+- } 9. Nxd7 Qxd7
10. Be3
{ A bit unusual thing about this opening is the queenside development comes first. }
10... Bg7 11. Rd1 Qc8 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O
{ White enjoys the bishop pair, safe king, and a lack of weaknesses. } 13... a6
{ •  13...Qf5  14.Bf3⩲  Assuming Black protects the knight on c6 @@StartBracket@@like Rfc8, for example@@EndBracket@@, our plan would be to play Nd5 and advance the pawns on the queenside.   •  13...e5?  Basically, Black is doing what we want them to do. Thank you for weakening the d5!  14.Bf3±  As in the game Jovanovic, Z @@StartBracket@@2556@@EndBracket@@-Raguz, D @@StartBracket@@2141@@EndBracket@@, Pula 2014. }
14. Qb3 Qc7 15. Bb6 Qc8 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5
{ With the bishop patrolling the d8 square, Black has a tough time getting their rooks active. }
