[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to Part Five"]
[Black "Introduction to Part Five"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d6 2. d4
{ We should stop Black from playing e7-e5 and winning the battle for the center at all cost. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...Nd7  3.e4  Black is already quite a bit worse @@StartBracket@@the knight on d7 looks ugly and White already dominates in the center@@EndBracket@@. We have decided to spend just a little bit of our time exploring this line in chapter 5.1 as we think it may be played by the less experienced players. }
3. Nc3
{ We like this approach the best. Our intentions are crystal clear - to play e2-e4 and establish a powerful center. }
3... g6
{ •  3...Bf5  4.Nh4  Whatever it takes to play e2-e4! By hitting the bishop on f5 early, we remove the last impediment from our way.   •  3...Nbd7  4.e4  e5  5.Rg1  A new unconventional way of playing against the Philidor Defense, which Yaro discovered after studying the games of DrNykerstein aka Magnus Carlsen on lichess.org. }
4. e4
{ This leads to a Pirc Defense. We consider Pirc being a dubious opening since Black gives away too much space way too soon. The intricate details of these particular lines of Pirc are succinctly covered in chapter 5.1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.1) 1...d6: Sidelines on move 2 and 3"]
[Black "2...Bg4 3.e4 Nd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d6
{ You are almost halfway through the course, good job, and keep it up! Part 5 will cover White's best responses vs. 1... d6. The important thing to remember is to play 2. d4, stopping Black from gaining too much space with e5. We offer a unique way of playing with 2... Nf6 @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3@@EndBracket@@, which will please anybody looking to escape the rut of the regular openings like King's Indian Defense. You will also see an unconventional way of playing vs. Philidor's Defense @@StartBracket@@that's right!@@EndBracket@@ with Carlsen's favorite @@StartBracket@@at least on lichess.org@@EndBracket@@ 5. Rg1, followed by 6. g4. While we try to stay unbiased, chapter 5 was the most fun one to write! }
2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... Bg4 3. e4
{ Since Black doesn't seem to mind, we grab some additional space in the center. }
3... Nd7
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.e4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. h3 { Kicking out the bishop from our territory } 4... Bxf3 5. Qxf3
{ Getting the bishop pair and a stable advantage. } 5... e5
{ Black has some other moves as well: ...c6, ...c5, ...e6, ...Ngf6, ...g6. Our plan remains the same in almost all cases:  Nc3, Be3, O-O-O. If they play c5, we should respond with a capture on c5. We have included a quick reference to 5... c5 in the next variation. }
6. Be3 { The plan: Nc3, O-O-O, g4. Attack on the kingside. } *

