2... Bg4 3. e4
{ Since Black doesn't seem to mind, we grab some additional space in the center. }
3... Nd7
{ 3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  g6  4.e4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. h3 { Kicking out the bishop from our territory } 4... Bh5 5. Nc3 e5
{ The only move that makes sense, at least trying to challenge White's center. }
6. g4 Bg6 7. h4 h6 { 7...h5  8.g5±  The plan: Be3, Qd2, O-O-O, Bh3. } 8. Qe2
{ We should prepare to castle long as soon as possible and then open up the d-file after d4xe5. This will create a powerful attack on the Black's king that is still stuck on e8.   We should also address a common concern: what happens to my bishop on f1, isn't it blocked now? We should point out that the bishop could be much better placed on h3 in the future, where @@StartBracket@@after Be3, O-O-O, and g5@@EndBracket@@ it could help us attack the knight on d7.   Another question could be: why not h5 immediately? We are saving h5 for later, giving the priority to a quick development with a long castle @@StartBracket@@bonus: make your opponent waste precious time thinking if h5 is going to happen at all or not@@EndBracket@@. Additionally, we are not scared if Black goes h5 themselves as we simply respond with g5, which would amplify our attack after Bh3. }
8... c6 9. h5 { Further expanding on the kingside. } 9... Bh7 10. dxe5
{ Opening up the d-file, which may come in handy after the long castle in a few moves. }
10... dxe5 11. g5 { The plan: Bd2, O-O-O, Bh3. } *

