1. Nf3 d6
{ You are almost halfway through the course, good job, and keep it up! Part 5 will cover White's best responses vs. 1... d6. The important thing to remember is to play 2. d4, stopping Black from gaining too much space with e5. We offer a unique way of playing with 2... Nf6 @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3@@EndBracket@@, which will please anybody looking to escape the rut of the regular openings like King's Indian Defense. You will also see an unconventional way of playing vs. Philidor's Defense @@StartBracket@@that's right!@@EndBracket@@ with Carlsen's favorite @@StartBracket@@at least on lichess.org@@EndBracket@@ 5. Rg1, followed by 6. g4. While we try to stay unbiased, chapter 5 was the most fun one to write! }
2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... f5 3. Nc3
{ We could also follow a setup suggested in 1... f5 chapter by playing 3. b3. However, we believe 3. Nc3 might be even a better option, enabling us to long castle rather quickly. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 { Allows us to damage Black's pawn structure. } 5. Bxf6 exf6
6. d5 { An important move, stopping Black from playing d5. } 6... Bg7 7. e3
{ We could also start with g3. You should be in a great shape as long as you remember to put the pawns primarily on the dark squares to compensate for the lack of the dark-squared bishop. }
7... O-O 8. g3
{ Overall, we prefer having the Nf3-g3-Bg2 setup, which is safer than leaving the pawn on g2 and developing the bishop on e2 @@StartBracket@@the bishop is closer to the king, serving as the king's most trusted bodyguard@@EndBracket@@. Our rationale for playing g3 is also to stop Black from potentially playing Bh6 and f4, thus undoubling the f-pawns and fixing their structure on the kingside. }
8... Nd7 9. Nd4 { Hoping Black will miss a fork on e6 :@@EndBracket@@ } 9...
Ne5 10. Bg2
{ The plan: O-O, Nce2, Nf4. We should also advance the pawns on the queenside like c4, b4, c5, whenever possible @@StartBracket@@after Rc1, for example@@EndBracket@@. }
