{ 2...g6  3.e4  Bg7  @@StartBracket@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  Bg7  3.d4  d6  4.Bc4 }
3. Nc3 Bf5 4. Nh4 { Pushing the bishop back and getting ready to play e4. }
4... Bd7
{ 4...Bc8  5.e4  e5  6.Nf3  Nbd7  7.Rg1  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3P4/2N2N2/PPP1PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  4.e4  e5  5.Rg1 }
5. e4 e5 6. Nf3
{ The knight has no use on h4 any longer, so we need to bring it back to participate in the fight for the center. }
6... exd4 7. Nxd4 g6
{ Reminds us of a Dragon variation in Sicilian Defense with one notable difference - the c-file is closed, which is suitable for White. }
8. f3
{ The immediate Be3 would run into Ng4, so we need to play f3. The pawn on f3 is a cornerstone of our attack on the kingside. }
8... Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. O-O-O
{ Unlike in Dragon, Black can't attack on the c-file after Rc8. The plan: g4, h4. }
