1. Nf3 d6
{ You are almost halfway through the course, good job, and keep it up! Chapter 14 will cover White's best responses vs. 1... d6. The important thing to remember is to play 2. d4, stopping Black from gaining too much space with e5. We offer a unique way of playing with 2... Nf6 @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3@@EndBracket@@, which will please anybody looking to escape the rut of the regular openings like King's Indian Defense. You will also see an unconventional way of playing vs. Philidor's Defense @@StartBracket@@that's right!@@EndBracket@@ with Carlsen's favorite @@StartBracket@@at least on lichess.org@@EndBracket@@ 5. Rg1, followed by 6. g4. While we try to stay unbiased, chapter 14 was the most fun one to write! }
2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...g6  3.e4  Bg7  @@StartBracket@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  Bg7  3.d4  d6  4.Bc4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. e4 e5
{ We are now in Phillidor's Defense domain. Our suggestion here is a far less explored line, leading to some sharp and active chess. }
5. Rg1
{ We have noticed this move while studying DrNykerstein games on lichess.org @@StartBracket@@allegedly, Magnus Carlsen's account@@EndBracket@@. White's idea is exactly what it appears to be - g4! }
5... c6 { One of the most 'Phillidor' moves. Black prepares b5. } 6. g4 h6 7.
Be3
{ 7.h4?  This natural move is a little premature.  7...exd4  8.Nxd4  Ne5  9.Be2  d5!  destroys our center.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxd5  Qxd5  12.Be3= }
7... b5 8. a3
{ Stopping Black from playing b4 is essential for the stability of our e4-pawn. }
8... Qc7 9. h4
{ Black doesn't have the same idea as earlier on move 7 @@StartBracket@@...exd4, ...Ne5, ...d5@@EndBracket@@, so now h4 is appropriate. }
9... Nb6 10. Nd2 { g5 wouldn't work as well because of Ng4. } 10... h5
{ Otherwise, g5 is powerful. } 11. gxh5 Rxh5 12. Bg5
{ Protecting the pawn and setting up a trap. } 12... Rh8
{ 12...exd4?  13.Nxb5!  A simple tactic, using the vulnerability of the rook on h5.  13...cxb5  14.Bxf6+- }
13. d5 a6 { The only way to protect the pawn on b5. } 14. dxc6 Qxc6 15. Qf3
{ White's game is a lot more pleasant. O-O-O and Bh3 is one of the potential plans. }
