2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...g6  3.e4  Bg7  @@StartBracket@@  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1ppbp/3p2p1/8/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Bc4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  Bg7  3.d4  d6  4.Bc4  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. e4 e5
{ We are now in Phillidor's Defense domain. Our suggestion here is a far less explored line, leading to some sharp and active chess. }
5. Rg1
{ We have noticed this move while studying DrNykerstein games on lichess.org @@StartBracket@@allegedly, Magnus Carlsen's account@@EndBracket@@. White's idea is exactly what it appears to be - g4! }
5... h5
{ One of the most aggressive attempts to fight against 5. Rg1. Black stops g4 for now. }
6. h3 { Preparing to play g4 one day. } 6... c6 7. a3
{ A useful waiting move.  7.g4?  leads to a forced draw.  7...hxg4  8.hxg4  exd4  9.Nxd4  Ne5  10.g5  Nfg4  11.f4  Seems like White is almost winning...  11...Qb6!  The move that refutes 7. g4. The X-ray on a7-g1 diagonal prevents us from taking on e5.  12.Be2   12.fxe5  dxe5  13.Rxg4  exd4  14.Nb1  Bb4+!  You will see later that 7. a3 was meant to stop this check.  15.c3  Bxg4  16.Qxg4  Bd6∓  12...Nh2  13.Rg3  Nhg4  14.Rg1=  White can't squeeze more than a draw out of this. }
7... b5 { Now g4 works just fine since Black doesn't have a check on b4. } 8.
g4 hxg4 9. hxg4 exd4 10. Nxd4 Ne5 11. g5 Nfg4 12. f4 Qb6
{ So far, the same line as 7. g4. } 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Rxg4 exd4 15. Na2
{ There is no check on b4 and the knight has a better spot on a2, not standing in the way of our long castle. }
15... Bxg4 16. Qxg4 { The plan: Bd2, O-O-O. } *

