{ You are almost halfway through the course, good job, and keep it up! Part five will cover White's best responses vs. 1... d6. The important thing to remember is to play 2. d4, stopping Black from gaining too much space with e5. We offer a unique way of playing with 2... Nf6 @@StartBracket@@3. Nc3@@EndBracket@@, which will please anybody looking to escape the rut of the regular openings like King's Indian Defense.  You will also see an unconventional way of playing vs. Philidor's Defense @@StartBracket@@that's right!@@EndBracket@@ with Carlsen's favorite @@StartBracket@@at least on lichess.org@@EndBracket@@ 5. Rg1, followed by 6. g4. While we try to stay unbiased, part five was the most fun one to write! }
2. d4 { Don't let them play e5 for free! Any other moves are vastly inferior. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. e4 Bg7 5. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4 in advance. } 5... O-O 6.
Bd3 c5 7. dxc5 dxc5 8. Be3
{ The pawn on c5 is a tangible weakness. Ideally, Black would like to have the pawns on e5 and c6. The pawn on c6 stops Nd5 ideas and the pawn on e5 prevents White from playing e5. }
8... Nfd7
{ 8...b6??  a huge blunder.  9.e5  Nd5  10.Be4+-  Some significant material gains are inevitable. }
9. a4 { Gaining some extra space on the queenside. } 9... b6
{ 9...Nc6  10.Bb5⩲ } 10. h4
{ The absence of the knight on f6 means h4-h5 should be played! This idea was frequently employed by the first world champion, William Steinitz. }
10... Nc6 11. h5 Nde5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Be2
{ Having a better game on both sides, the queen trade doesn't scare us. } 13...
Bb7 14. a5
{ We could further expand with f4 and e5. Short castle could be okay, too. } *

