1. Nf3 d6 2. d4 Nd7
{ A passive move, which may lead us to a bad version of the Philidor's Defense. }
3. e4 e5 4. dxe5 { The most straightforward and forcing approach. } 4... dxe5
5. Bc4 h6
{ Loses just like  5...Be7  and  5...Ngf6  but in a lot more intricate way. }
6. Bxf7+ { Asking the king to go down a rabbit hole. } 6... Kxf7 7. Nxe5+ Kf6
{ 7...Nxe5  8.Qxd8+-  Wins the queen and the game. } 8. Nc3
{ A magnificent knight sacrifice. } 8... Kxe5
{ Accepting a Trojan horse may have its merits only if Black has too much confidence or seriously doubts your attacking skills. }
9. Qd5+ { Starting an exciting king chase. } 9... Kf6 10. Qf5+ Ke7 11. Nd5+
{ The knight joins the attack and pushes the king even further away from the other pieces. }
11... Kd6 12. Bf4+
{ Getting the third piece in. It makes sense to have at least 3 pieces in attack to maximize your chances for success. }
12... Kc6 13. Qe6+ Bd6 14. Nb4+
{ The key move to remember. Otherwise, our attack may stall a little. } 14...
Kb6 15. Bxd6 Ndf6
{ 15...cxd6  lets us push the king to a5, where it will get checkmated soon.  16.Qxd6+  Ka5  17.Nd5+- }
16. Bc5+ { The only winning move! } 16... Kxc5 17. Nd3+ Qxd3
{ 17...Kb5  18.a4+  Ka5  19.b4# } 18. Qe5+ Kc6 19. cxd3
{ The plan: Rc1, O-O, f4, and advance the d, e, and f pawns. } *

