1. Nf3 f5
{ It's finally the time to consider 1... f5, which, at the risk of sounding like Captain Obvious, could be played by anyone ordinarily playing the Dutch Defense. We like 2.b3 here with the future d2-d4 at some point. The most recurring theme in this Part 6 - we will be aiming to push e2-e4 quite often, which will open up the e-file and will help us exploit the weakness of the Black's pawn either on e7 or e6 @@StartBracket@@depending where Black puts it@@EndBracket@@. }
2. b3 Nf6
{ 2...d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Bb2  g6  5.e3  The bishop usually needs to stay away from g2 in this particular move order because Black may be able to push e5-e4 and make it highly ineffective. We look into this setup deeply in chapter 6.2. }
3. Bb2 e6
{ Playing  3...g6  would make little sense since we can take the knight with  4.Bf6  thus ruining Black's pawn structure. }
4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. d4
{ Whenever the pawn moves to d6, we should always play d4, stopping Black from making further advances in the center with e6-e5. }
7... Qe8 8. c4
{ This position is so crucial that we have decided to split it into two chapters - 6.1 and 6.2. Chapter 6.1 will explore White's ideas after ...Qh5, ...a5, ...Nbd7, and ...c6. Chapter 6.2 will cover the remaining moves - ...Bd8, ...Ne4, ...Nc6, and ...Qg6. }
