1. Nf3
{ In this chapter, we will consider Dutch-related structures arising after 1... f5. We recommend sticking with 2. b3 - our favorite bishop fianchetto. One major takeaway from this chapter: always aim to break in the center with e4! We especially recommend studying the game after 8. c4 closely. To make these lines more digestible for the learners, we have split them into two parts - chapter 6.1 and chapter 6.2. }
1... f5
{ Black attempts to play the Dutch Defense, which is generally considered a risky, speculative opening. We will deviate from the main lines and instead explore less analyzed and more exciting ideas after 2. b3 }
2. b3 g6
{ One of the worst moves, leading to a damaged pawn structure for Black. } 3.
Bb2 Nf6 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3
{ Placing more pawns on the dark squares, compensating for the lack of the bishop. }
5... d5 6. d4 Bd6 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 { The plan: O-O, c4, Nc3. } *

