{ 6...Qe8  7.c4  Qh5  @@StartBracket@@  7...d6  8.d4  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppppb1pp/4pn2/5p1q/2P5/1P3NP1/PB1PPPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d4  d6  9.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.   6...Nc6  the knight doesn't belong on c6.  7.c4  d6  8.d4±  The plan: Nc3, d5, Rc1. }
7. d4 Ne4
{ A little premature knight move, looking especially strange considering Black's undeveloped queenisde. }
8. Nbd2 Bf6 { 8...d5  gives away the e5-square.  9.Ne5  Nd7  10.Nd3± } 9. Ne1
{ Immediately challenging the strong e4-knight. } 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 e5
{ Surprisingly, leads to a lost position for Black pretty much by the move 15. }
11. dxe5 dxe5
{ Taking with the bishop on e5 would have lost a pawn after Qd5 - double attack on the king and the bishop. }
12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nd3 Nc6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Rfe1
{ 15.Nxe5  Also works, although winning might be somewhat tougher than after 15. Rfe1.  15...Ba6  16.Rfe1  Rd2  17.Nf3  Fighting against a bishop pair in the endgames is a fool's errand. We facilitate some trades, leading to a rook and knight versus rook and bishop endgame.  17...Bxb2  18.Nxd2  Bxa1  19.Rxa1± }
15... Re8 { 15...e4  16.Bxf6  gxf6  17.Nf4± } 16. e4
{ Breaking Black's center. } 16... fxe4 17. Nc5 Bf5 18. Nxe4
{ The plan: Re2, Rae1. } *

