3. Bb2 e6 4. g3 Be7
{ •  4...b6  5.Bg2  Bb7  6.O-O  Be7  7.c4  O-O  8.d3  transposes to  4...Be7  5.Bg2  O-O  6.O-O  b6  7.c4  Bb7  8.d3   •  4...g6  looks odd to combine both ...e6 and ...g6.  5.Bg2  Bg7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  This line is a no-brainer. We suggest winning some space with c4, d4, Nc3, Qc2, e4.  7...d6  8.d4  Qe7  9.Nc3⩲   •  4...d6  5.d4  Be7  6.Bg2  O-O  7.O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ 6...Qe8  7.c4  Qh5  @@StartBracket@@  7...d6  8.d4  transposes to the mainline.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppppb1pp/4pn2/5p1q/2P5/1P3NP1/PB1PPPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.d4  d6  9.Nc3  transposes to the mainline.   6...Nc6  the knight doesn't belong on c6.  7.c4  d6  8.d4±  The plan: Nc3, d5, Rc1. }
7. d4 Qe8 8. c4 Bd8 { Preparing e5 in the future. } 9. Nc3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11.
e4 { Stopping Black from playing e4. } 11... f4 { Loses a pawn. } 12. Ba3 Be7
{ 12...Rf7  13.Nxe5!  Qxe5  14.Qxd8++- } 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd5
{ The key move, winning a pawn. If we fail to make it, Black could be even better after c6 and Bg4. }
14... Nxd5 15. Qxd5+ Kh8 16. Qxe5
{ The queen trade is pretty much unavoidable, thus our extra pawn should give us a close-to-winning game. In case Black tries Qd8 now, we can proceed with Rad1, then move the queen out of the way, and push e5. }
