Bb2 Nf6 4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3
{ Placing more pawns on the dark squares, compensating for the lack of the bishop. }
5... d5 6. d4 Bd6 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 { The plan: O-O, c4, Nc3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.3) 1...f5 2.b3 d6"]
[Black "3...Nf6 4.Bb2 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. b3 d6
{ Most of the time this move transposes to 2...Nf6. We will look into the lines that are not related. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 5. e3
{ The bishop usually needs to stay away from g2 because Black may be able to push e5-e4 and make it highly ineffective. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O e6
{ Leads to a strange mix of Dutch and so-called "hedgehog" pawn formation where the majority of the pawns will reside on the 6th rank. }
8. c4 b6 9. Nc3 Qe7 10. Ng5
{ Mainly preparing Bf3 but also could play f4 and gain some space. } 10... h6
11. Nh3 g5 12. f4 { Securing a safe spot for the knight. } 12... g4 13. Nf2 Bb7
14. Qc2 { The plan: Rae1 and e4. } *

