[Black "3...Nf6 4.Bb2 g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. b3 d6
{ Most of the time this move transposes to 2...Nf6. We will look into the lines that are not related. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 5. e3
{ The bishop usually needs to stay away from g2 because Black may be able to push e5-e4 and make it highly ineffective. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O e6
{ Leads to a strange mix of Dutch and so-called "hedgehog" pawn formation where the majority of the pawns will reside on the 6th rank. }
8. c4 b6 9. Nc3 Qe7 10. Ng5
{ Mainly preparing Bf3 but also could play f4 and gain some space. } 10... Bb7
11. Bf3
{ Trading Black's most active piece and eliminating any chances to get accidentally checkmated on g2. }
11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 c6 13. h4
{ An important move, stopping Black from playing h6 and g5. } 13... h6 14. Nh3
e5 15. Rad1
{ The plan could be g3, Kg2, Rd2, Rfd1. Whenever Black goes e4, we get a nice spot on f4 for our knight on h3. }
*

