1. Nf3 f5 2. b3 d6
{ Most of the time this move transposes to 2...Nf6. We will look into the lines that are not related. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 5. e3
{ The bishop usually needs to stay away from g2 because Black may be able to push e5-e4 and make it highly ineffective. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Ne4 8. Nbd2
{ We would like to get rid of the knight on e4 as soon as possible. Yaro, one of the authors, likes to follow the ' rule of 2 ': whenever they cross the middle line, try to attack or trade those pieces within the 2 moves. }
8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2
{ Black hardly has any play, while our plan is pretty straightforward: c4, b4, Rac1, Rfd1, d5, and attack on the queenside. }
