1. Nf3 f5 2. b3 d6
{ Most of the time this move transposes to 2...Nf6. We will look into the lines that are not related. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 5. e3
{ The bishop usually needs to stay away from g2 because Black may be able to push e5-e4 and make it highly ineffective. }
5... Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O b6
{ An impatient move, trying to fianchetto the bishop before having any grip on the center. }
8. d5
{ Now ...Bb7 is not happening since we have c4 and Ng5, hitting e6 hard. } 8...
e5 9. dxe6 Bxe6 { Loses rather quickly. } 10. Ng5
{ Now Black can't keep up with our threats. } 10... Bf7 11. Nxf7 Kxf7
{ Loses in pretty much exactly the same way as the rook capture. } 12. Bc4+ d5
13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Bxd5+ Kg7 15. Bxa8 Bxa1 16. c3
{ A cherry on top: in addition to the extra pawn, the bishop on a1 may never get back into the game. }
