[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to Part Seven"]
[Black "Introduction to Part Seven"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now, it's the time to consider the last remaining moves that happen rarely. We decided to group them in Part 7 - The Sidelines. }
1. Nf3 Nc6
{ •  1...b6  2.e4  c5   2...Bb7  3.Nc3  White normally enjoys a decent advantage here. We show how to get there in chapter 7.2.  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Transposes the game into Sicilian Defense with a rare b6 move. We would suggest memorizing a few lines here, covered in chapter 7.3. Sicilians always require some memorization, even the objectively inferior ones, since the sharpness of the game dictates the need for precision.   •  1...b5  The least challenging move in the entire course. We can only imagine this one being played online in the hyper-quick time control games.  2.e4!  One of the very few times where 2. e4 is a great idea. Chapter 7.4 provides an example of how to get a much better game versus 1... b5. }
2. d4 d5 3. c4
{ Out of the remaining few chapters, we suggest focusing on chapter 7.1 the most. Please examine how to fight versus the Chigorin Defense and study the model games carefully in the Model Games chapter of the course. A word of caution: the Chigorin Defense can be tricky if you don't memorize the first 8-9 moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.1) 1...Nc6"]
[Black "2...d5 3.c4 e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nc6
{ Have you expected to learn Chigorin Defense in this course? Neither have we expected to write about it :@@EndBracket@@ After  1...Nc6  , White's best option is to play  2.d4  @@StartBracket@@stopping Black from playing e5 is crucial@@EndBracket@@. We would recommend primarily focusing on 3... Bg4. In some cases, we get double pawns on the f-file, which will help us fight for the center and attack on the g-file.   In the main line, we leave the king in the center for an extended time, since it's the safest behind the pawn wall. The 3... Nf6 line would require a bit of memorization - but once you learn it, you may get a winning position almost right out of the opening. }
2. d4
{ We transpose to the Chigorin Defense, rarely played on a high level.   2.b3?!  doesn't make much sense anymore since Black can easily grab some space after  2...e5  3.Bb2  e4  4.Nd4  Nxd4  5.Bxd4  d5  6.e3 }
2... d5 3. c4 e6 4. a3
{ Once we stop Bf8-b4, Black's options become quite limited. } 4... dxc4 5. e4
{ We are getting the pawn back pretty easily. Note how easy it is to play when Black can't challenge our center with c5 - the main drawback of the knight being on c6. }
5... b5 6. a4
{ We need to win the pawn back immediately. If we hesitate for a moment, Black will play Rb8 and a6, keeping an extra pawn. }
6... Ba6
{ Holding on to the pawn only makes things worse for Black.   6...b4  7.Bxc4±  White has a comfortable advantage due to a bulletproof center - d4 and e4. }
7. axb5 Bxb5 8. b3 { Taking advantage of the pin. } 8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10.
Qxd2 Nf6 11. Nc3
{ We will get a pawn back on the next move. Black's bishop also looks like it's getting lost. }
*

