1. Nf3 Nc6
{ Have you expected to learn Chigorin Defense in this course? Neither have we expected to write about it :@@EndBracket@@ After  1...Nc6  , White's best option is to play  2.d4  @@StartBracket@@stopping Black from playing e5 is crucial@@EndBracket@@. We would recommend primarily focusing on 3... Bg4. In some cases, we get double pawns on the f-file, which will help us fight for the center and attack on the g-file.   In the main line, we leave the king in the center for an extended time, since it's the safest behind the pawn wall. The 3... Nf6 line would require a bit of memorization - but once you learn it, you may get a winning position almost right out of the opening. }
2. d4
{ We transpose to the Chigorin Defense, rarely played on a high level.   2.b3?!  doesn't make much sense anymore since Black can easily grab some space after  2...e5  3.Bb2  e4  4.Nd4  Nxd4  5.Bxd4  d5  6.e3 }
2... d5 3. c4 Nf6
{ A risky approach. Giving up so much control in the center can hardly be recommended. }
4. cxd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qa5 6. Bd2 Qf5 7. Rc1
{ A logical development. The rook will attack on the c-file and prevent Nb4. }
7... e6 8. g4 { We need to take advantage of the queen being misplaced on f5. }
8... Nxg4 9. e4 Qf6
{ 9...Qh5  doesn't help:  10.h3  Nf6  11.Nb5+-  Bd6  won't ease the pain since we got e5, attacking the bishop and the knight on f6. }
10. Nb5 Qd8 11. d5 { A timely pawn break in the center. } 11... exd5 12. exd5
a6 { Moving the knight away from c6 would have run into Nc7. } 13. dxc6 axb5
14. Qe2+ Qe7
{ 14...Be7  15.cxb7  Bxb7  16.Qxb5++-  White wins the bishop on b7. } 15. cxb7
Bxb7 16. Rxc7 { We can now fully appreciate early 7. Rc1. } 16... Qxe2+ 17.
Bxe2
{ The material is even but Black's king is getting destroyed. Hence, White should be winning. The plan is the obvious Bb5 and the short castle, bringing the rook to e1 afterward. }
