1. Nf3 Nc6
{ Have you expected to learn Chigorin Defense in this course? Neither have we expected to write about it :@@EndBracket@@ After  1...Nc6  , White's best option is to play  2.d4  @@StartBracket@@stopping Black from playing e5 is crucial@@EndBracket@@. We would recommend primarily focusing on 3... Bg4. In some cases, we get double pawns on the f-file, which will help us fight for the center and attack on the g-file.   In the main line, we leave the king in the center for an extended time, since it's the safest behind the pawn wall. The 3... Nf6 line would require a bit of memorization - but once you learn it, you may get a winning position almost right out of the opening. }
2. d4
{ We transpose to the Chigorin Defense, rarely played on a high level.   2.b3?!  doesn't make much sense anymore since Black can easily grab some space after  2...e5  3.Bb2  e4  4.Nd4  Nxd4  5.Bxd4  d5  6.e3 }
2... d5 3. c4 dxc4
{ A mix of Chigorin Defense and Queen's Gambit Accepted doesn't work out. Normally, it's best to stick to the standard opening plans. }
4. d5 { We need to take advantage of the exposed knight and gain some space. }
4... Nb8 { 4...Nb4  loses the knight instantly.  5.Qa4+  c6  6.Qxb4+- } 5. e4
Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Bxc4 exd5 8. Nxd5
{ The only move that makes sense. Taking on d5 with the pawn would upset our bishop on c4. }
8... Nxd5 9. O-O
{ A stunning example of the delayed capture concept. Instead of making 'an obvious' move, look around and figure out if you can do something a little unconventional and creative.   9.Bxd5  leads to a tiny bit better game for White.  9...Bb4+  That's the issue with capturing the knight on d5 too soon: Black checks, trades the bishops, and hopes for an endgame.  10.Bd2  Bxd2+  11.Qxd2  c6  12.Bc4  Qxd2+  13.Kxd2⩲  In case you forget the main line and somehow end up here @@StartBracket@@even the authors themselves forget things, believe it or not :@@EndBracket@@ @@EndBracket@@, the plan is Rad1, Kc1, Rhe1. }
9... Nf6 10. Bxf7+
{ Thank you, Gioacchino Greco, for inventing this sacrifice over 400 years ago. }
10... Ke7
{ 10...Kxf7  11.Qxd8+-  An extra queen after 11 moves  = great success. } 11.
Qb3 Nc6
{ 11...c6  We don't know a single person who would make this move but provide it here for the sake of completeness. Good news: you don't need to memorize it!  12.e5  Ne4  Otherwise, Bg5 would be really bad news for Black.  13.Ng5  The knight on g5 defends the bishop on f7 and makes our queen free to go anywhere and pursue the new attacking opportunities.  13...Nc5  14.Qb4  Nba6  15.Qh4+-  We have way too many discovered checks here. }
12. e5 Ne4 13. Bd5
{ Now you can see why we provided some lines after 11... c6 - it stopped Bd5. }
13... Bf5 14. Bxe4
{ Eliminating the knight and winning the queen on the next move:  14...Bxe4  15.Bg5+  Ke8  16.Bxd8+- }
*

