1. Nf3 b6
{ While not the best,  1...b6  happens quite a bit in online games. In chapters 7.2 and 7.3, we will learn how to gain a sizable advantage against this objectively dubious move. Chapter 7.2 will cover 2... Bb7 and 2... e6 - the most common moves. Not surprisingly, we would suggest that you spend the majority of your study time here in this current chapter. Chapter 7.3 will show you how to get beyond comfortable against the rarest moves after 1. Nf3 b6 2. e4. }
2. e4 { The most direct way to refute Black's questionable opening strategy. }
2... e6 3. d4
{ We can develop even more comfortably than in the mainline. The pawn can be put on c3 now to protect the center even more and the knight on b1 can move to d2, followed by either e5-Ne4 or Re1-Nf1-Ng3. }
3... d5
{ Resembles a weird mix between Scandinavian and French, with a useless inclusion of b6. As discussed previously, mixing too many openings is never a good idea. }
4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Bf4 Qe4+
{ From here, we can attempt all sorts of great ideas: Bb5, Qf3, or just a simple development after Nc3, Qd2, O-O-O. }
6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bd3 Qb7
{ Queen fianchetto is a sad necessity, Other squares would have left Black's queens overly exposed to White's attacks. }
8. O-O { The plan: c4, Nc3, Re1, Bg5. } *

