1. Nf3 b6
{ While not the best,  1...b6  happens quite a bit in online games. In chapters 7.2 and 7.3, we will learn how to gain a sizable advantage against this objectively dubious move. Chapter 7.2 will cover 2... Bb7 and 2... e6 - the most common moves. Not surprisingly, we would suggest that you spend the majority of your study time here in this current chapter. Chapter 7.3 will show you how to get beyond comfortable against the rarest moves after 1. Nf3 b6 2. e4. }
2. e4 { The most direct way to refute Black's questionable opening strategy. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Too risky. } 4. e5 { Challenge accepted! } 4... Ne4 5.
Ne2
{ Avoiding trading the knights and preparing to push the knight on e4 around after d3. }
5... e6 6. d3 Nc5 7. d4 Ne4 8. Nf4
{ We have succesfully gained a tempo on d3-d4 operation. Now, the idea is to finish developing the kingside and further attack the knight on e4. Our knight on f4 will be a valuable asset for the kingside attack. }
8... Be7 9. c3 { An extra protection for the center. } 9... O-O 10. Bd3 d5 11.
O-O
{ We could play Nd2, get rid of the knight on e4, and attack after Qg4 or Qh5. }
