1. Nf3 b6
{ While not the best,  1...b6  happens quite a bit in online games. In chapters 7.2 and 7.3, we will learn how to gain a sizable advantage against this objectively dubious move. Chapter 7.2 will cover 2... Bb7 and 2... e6 - the most common moves. Not surprisingly, we would suggest that you spend the majority of your study time here in this current chapter. Chapter 7.3 will show you how to get beyond comfortable against the rarest moves after 1. Nf3 b6 2. e4. }
2. e4 { The most direct way to refute Black's questionable opening strategy. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 Nf6 { Too risky. } 4. e5 { Challenge accepted! } 4... Nd5 5.
Nxd5 Bxd5 6. d4 e6 7. Bf4
{ 7.Bd3?  runs into  7...c5!  and Black can successfully target our center after Nc6 on the next move. }
7... Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. c3
{ Preparing Qc2. Sometimes, we could also play Bc2, Qd3. } 9... c5 10. Qc2 h6
{ We assume your opponent is not in a charitable spirit, and will protect the hanging pawn. }
11. Bh7+
{ Pushing the king to h8 is helpful for the future attack. In addition, if the game ever goes deep into an endgame, the king will have a harder time getting to the center where it belongs. }
11... Kh8 12. Be4
{ Trading Black's most active piece and completely erasing the last vestiges of their initiative. }
12... Bxe4
{ 12...Nc6  leads to an irrevocably damaged pawn structure for Black.  13.Bxd5  exd5  14.dxc5  Opening up the file and exposing Black's pawns on d5 and d7.  14...bxc5  15.O-O± }
13. Qxe4 Nc6 14. d5 exd5 15. Qxd5 { The plan: O-O, Rad1, Rfe1. } *

