{ While not the best,  1...b6  happens quite a bit in online games. In chapters 7.2 and 7.3, we will learn how to gain a sizable advantage against this objectively dubious move. Chapter 7.2 will cover 2... Bb7 and 2... e6 - the most common moves. Not surprisingly, we would suggest that you spend the majority of your study time here in this current chapter. Chapter 7.3 will show you how to get beyond comfortable against the rarest moves after 1. Nf3 b6 2. e4. }
2. e4 { The most direct way to refute Black's questionable opening strategy. }
2... Bb7 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...c5  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p1pppppp/1p6/8/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq e3 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...c5  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bb7  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@see the variation@@EndBracket@@. }
4. d4 Bb4
{ •  4...c5  5.d5±  Kills the bishop. The plan is the usual Be3, Qd2, O-O-O.   •  4...g6  5.Bg5  ruins Black's plans for ...Bg7.  5...Be7  6.h4±   •  4...Ne7  5.d5  Ng6  6.h4!±  The plan: h5 @@StartBracket@@if Black allows@@EndBracket@@, Bg5, Qd2, O-O-O. }
5. Bd3 Nf6 6. Nd2 { The best defense of the e4. } 6... d5 7. e5 Ne4 8. Qg4 g6
9. Ncxe4 dxe4 10. Bb5+
{ 10.Bxe4?  is not so clear.  10...Bxd2+  11.Bxd2  Qxd4 } 10... c6
{ 10...Kf8  11.c3  Be7  12.Nxe4+-  White is a pawn up and also strategically winning. }
11. Be2 Bxd2+ { 11...Qxd4  12.c3+-  wins a piece. } 12. Bxd2 Qc7 13. O-O-O
{ White is likely to win the pawn on e4. The weakness of the dark squares will cost Black dearly. }
