1. Nf3 b6 2. e4 c5
{ • This move transposes the game into Sicilian Defense with a rare b6 move.  2...g6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/5N2/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 1@@EndFEN@@  1...g6  2.e4  b6   •  2...d6  You may wonder if Black just likes their pawns on the dark squares and will follow up with 3... f6 and then 4... h6? :@@EndBracket@@ We don't know for sure. In any case, this move doesn't put any pressure on White and allows us to develop in any way we please.  3.d4  Bb7  4.Bd3±  We would recommend playing c4 and Nc3, gaining as much space as possible. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7
{ Anything else would raise the questions why b6 was even played in the first place. }
5. Nc3 e6 6. Ndb5
{ Targeting d6 and preparing Bf4, which would tighten our grip on Black's weak dark squares. }
6... d6 7. Bf4 e5 8. Nd5
{ A nice in-between move, winning the game. The lesson here: check if you can attack your opponent before running away from their threats. Half of the time you'll notice your opponent's threats are not even real! }
8... exf4 { 8...Na6  9.Be3+-  The plan: Qd2, O-O-O. } 9. Nbc7+ Kd7
{ The alternative of giving away the queen on c7 obviously loses, so let's enjoy a checkmate in a few moves. }
10. Qg4+ Kc6 11. Bb5+ Kc5 12. b4+
{ Pushing the king even further into the wilderness:  12...Kd4  13.Rd1+  Ke5  14.Qxf4# }
