1. Nf3
{ In our final chapter, we are going to face the least challenging first move. We have covered a lot of ground, so let's finish with a line that is pleasant, enjoyable and something we can certainly beat! }
1... b5
{ One of least challenging moves. No wonder that this chapter is going to be the shortest. Our path to advantage is crystal clear. }
2. e4 Bb7 { We will consider the most principled and aggressive approach. } 3.
Bxb5 Bxe4 4. O-O
{ We know that we need to castle for sure. Everything is secondary and can played later. First things first. }
4... c6
{ This continuation has slightly better statistics than a mainline but is rarely played. }
5. Ba4 Nf6 6. d4 e6 7. c4 { We are preparing Nc3 and a pawn break - d5! } 7...
Be7 8. Nc3 Bxf3 { This is hardly any better. } 9. Qxf3 d5
{ Black has stopped us from playing d5 but the huge price. We now enjoy a bishop pair advantage and an open file after trading the pawns on d5. In addition, the pawn on c6 is also a significant weakness and can be targeted after Ra1-c1 later, if needed. }
10. cxd5 exd5 11. Re1 O-O 12. Bg5
{ The plan: Re2, Rae1, Bc2, and attack on the kingside. } *

