1. Nf3
{ In our final chapter, we are going to face the least challenging first move. We have covered a lot of ground, so let's finish with a line that is pleasant, enjoyable and something we can certainly beat! }
1... b5
{ One of least challenging moves. No wonder that this chapter is going to be the shortest. Our path to advantage is crystal clear. }
2. e4 Bb7 { We will consider the most principled and aggressive approach. } 3.
Bxb5 Bxe4 4. O-O
{ We know that we need to castle for sure. Everything is secondary and can played later. First things first. }
4... Nf6 5. d4 e6 6. c4 { Grabbing all the space we can. } 6... Be7 7. Nc3 Bb7
8. Re1 O-O 9. Ba4
{ The bishop on b5 is useless, so we transfer it to a4 and later to c2 if the need arises. }
9... d6
{ 9...d5  doesn't work well.  10.c5  Ne4  11.Ne5+-  Black's development is severely crippled. }
10. d5 e5 11. c5
{ The key move, making this whole line with b5, Bb7, and Be4 unplayable. }
11... c6
{ 11...Na6  12.c6  Bc8  13.Bc2+-  The plan: a3, b4, Nc4, b5, and advance on the queenside. }
12. Qb3 { The queen effectively comes into the game. } 12... Qc8 13. cxd6
{ Opening up the files and getting ready for Nxe5, Bg5, and Rac1. } 13... Bxd6
14. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ 14...cxd5  15.Bg5+-  White is winning due to multiple life-threatening ideas like Bf6 and Rac1. Black is pretty much still down a few pieces as the queenside remains undeveloped. }
15. Rxe5 cxd5 16. Bg5 Nbd7 17. Bxd7
{ The only move! Otherwise, Black is still worse but far from lost. } 17...
Nxd7 18. Nxd5 { A nice tactic, giving us a decisive advantage. } 18... Bxd5
{ 18...Nxe5  19.Ne7++- } 19. Rxd5
{ White is technically winning. We need to bring the bishop back to e3, rook to c1, and gradually win the endgame after the queen trade.   If you are reading this, we assume you either have finished the course or simply clicked on the last chapter out of curiosity about what kind of move 1... b5 is :@@EndBracket@@ Either way, congratulations! We are pleased that you have chosen to give this repertoire a shot, and hope it will serve you very well.   One last thing: remember to review the chapters of this course from time to time @@StartBracket@@say, every 2-3 weeks@@EndBracket@@. You would be amazed how quickly even we, the authors, are able to forget things, so some spaced repetition would help you remember the materials covered in the chapters infinitely better. On this note, good luck with your chess, and have fun! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Zherebukh, Y. vs. Ioannidis, E., Dusseldorf 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ We believe in this system! Here you can see one of the authors, Yaro, playing 1. Nf3-2. b3 at the World Cup 2021 after a year-long pause in tournament play, caused by the pandemic. }
1... d5 2. b3 Bf5 3. Bb2 e6 4. g3 h6 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nbd2
{ A pretty standard setup, aiming for the eventual e2-e4 break. } 8... a5 9. a3
{ Whenever they play a5, go a3! The idea is to block Black's pawn on a4 and meet a5-a4 with b3-b4 expansion on the queenside. }
9... a4
{ As you will see, the pawn on  a4  will become one of the Black's biggest weaknesses in the middlegame. Perhaps, Black should have been a bit more modest.  9...c6  10.Re1  Bh7  11.e4  White's plan here could be Qe2, e5, and then the attack on the kingside launched after h4. }
10. b4 c5 11. bxc5 Nc6
{ 11...Bxc5  The best option is to do a straightforward capture on c5.  12.Bd4  We still prefer White. The plan is crystal clear: Rb1, c4, and pressure Black on the queenside. }
12. Nd4
{ Now Black can't simply win the pawn on c5 back.  12.d4  Saving the pawn would open up the bishop on f5 and give Black a good compensation.  12...b6! }
12... Nxd4
{ 12...Bxc5  13.Nxf5  exf5  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.Bxd5±   14...gxf6  15.e3  Black's pawn structure undoubtedly wins the prize for the worst pawn structure ever! }
13. Bxd4 Rc8 14. Rb1
{ Targeting the b7 and getting ready to double up on the open file. } 14... Qd7
15. c4 { Helps us open up the bishop on g2. } 15... Bxc5 16. Bxc5 Rxc5 17. Rb4
Ra8 18. Qb1 { The queen finally gets to make its first move as well. } 18...
Rb8 19. Qb2 { Preparing Rfb1. } 19... dxc4 20. Rxc4
{ Trading one rook pair helps us mitigate Black's counterplay. } 20... Rcc8 21.
Rxc8+
{ 21.Rd4  Unfortunately, Yaro missed an immediate win.  21...Qe8  22.Nc4  Nd6 is unstoppable and, at the very least, Black will lose the a4. }
21... Rxc8 22. Nc4 Rc7 23. Nb6 Qe8 24. Re1
{ An interesting idea, but not allowing Black to play e6-e5 was much easier.   24.Nc4  Qd7  25.h3±  Black has issues with finding the next move that makes sense. Meanwhile, White is ready to play Rb1 and start picking up Black's weak pawns on b7 and, eventually, a4. }
24... e5 25. e4 Bd7
{ 25...Be6  26.Qxe5  Rc2  27.Qd4  White saw this position during the game but misevaluated this as winning. Surprisingly, Stockfish only gives White a slight edge if Black goes Nf6-g4 on the next move. }
26. Nc4 Be6 27. Nxe5 Bb3 28. Nc4 Bxc4
{ A decisive mistake.  28...Qb5  29.Qd2±  Otherwise, Black goes Bc4 and wins a piece since the queen on b2 would have been unprotected. If Black takes on c4 and gets back a pawn, we push e5 and gain a considerable advantage in space. }
29. dxc4 Rxc4 30. e5
{ White now dominates everywhere and has a way safer king. Game over. } 30...
b5 31. Kf1
{ A beautiful move, aiming to protect the rook on e1, which enables a capture on f6. }
31... Nh7 32. Bd5 Rc5 33. Qd4 Qe7 34. e6 f6 35. Ba2 { Threatening Qc5. } 35...
Kf8 { 35...Ng5  36.Qxc5  Qxc5  37.e7+  Kh7  38.e8=Q+- } 36. Qe4 g5 37. Qg6 Rc7
38. Rd1
{ Black has no useful moves, so they decided to stop the pain and resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nakamura, H. vs. Caruana, F., Saint Louis 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 c5 3. Bb2 { 3.e3!  Way more precise than 3.Bb2. } 3... Nc6
{ 3...f6!  Black had a chance to occupy the center with this move, trying to go e5 next. }
4. e3 a6 { Otherwise, White gets a comfortable play after Bb5. } 5. d4 cxd4 6.
Nxd4 Nf6 7. Nxc6
{ The point of this trade is to isolate the pawn on a6 and potentially have a pawn majority attack in the endgame - a2-b3 vs. a6. }
7... bxc6 8. Nd2 e6 9. Bd3
{ 9.c4  is also possible. We like this move slightly better since it keeps Black guessing where we will put the bishop - on d3 or e2. }
9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. c4 a5 12. Qc2
{ A second alternative we like  12.Rc1  Bb7  13.cxd5  cxd5  14.Nf3⩲  We can go Ne5, Bd4, f4, and have a slightly better game due to a better position in the center and a pawn majority - a2-b3 vs. a5. }
12... h6 13. Nf3 Ba6 14. e4
{ A typical idea; however, it feels a bit rushed here.  14.Ne5  Qb6  15.Rac1⩲  A less commital approach that we like. White still can go f4-f5 in the future or even do something a little unorthodox - Kh1, Rg1, g4, and attack on the kingside! }
14... Qb6 15. Rfe1 Rfd8 16. Rac1 Rac8 17. c5 { 17.Ne5  is still preferable. }
17... Qb7
{ 17...Bxd3!  Black missed a chance to get a great game. Most likely, Caruana miscalculated somewhere along the next 10 moves.  18.cxb6  Bxc2  19.Bxf6  gxf6  20.Rxc2  Bb4  This move could have been overlooked by both players. Now, playing Re2 isn't an option since Black can take on e4 and deliver a deadly Rd1 next.  21.b7  Rc7  22.Rd1  c5  23.exd5  Rxb7  24.d6  Rbd7  25.Kf1  White loses a pawn but the game is still closer to a draw than Black's win.  25...Rxd6  26.Rxd6  Rxd6  27.Ke2⩱  White has a good chance for a draw due to Black's weakened pawn structure. }
18. Bxa6 Qxa6 19. Bxf6
{ Since the pawn is going to e5 inevitably, we need to get rid of the bishop beforehand, so it doesn't get blocked by its own pawn. }
19... Bxf6 20. e5 Be7
{ 20...Bg5  The only chance for Black to stay in the game. The key is to gain a tempo by pushing the rook away from c1, thus being able to attack the pawn on c5 more effectively.  21.Nxg5   21.Rcd1  Be7!  22.Nd4  Qa7  23.Rc1  Bg5!  24.Rcd1  Be7  25.Rc1  Bg5=  White can't avoid the repetition, so needs to accept a draw.  hxg5  22.Qd2  d4  23.Qxg5  Rd5  24.Rcd1⩲  White's plan is a rook lift to e4 and then g4. Objectively, Black can hold according to Stockfish. However, it is extremely unlikely to happen in a real chess game. }
21. Nd4
{ From now on, this is a piece of cake for White. We will see a classic example 'Good knight vs. Bad Bishop'. }
21... Rd7 22. f4 Rb7 23. a3
{ Nakamura prepares to play b4 in case Black ever wants to play a4. } 23...
Rcb8 24. Re3 Rb5
{ A desperate attempt in a lost position.  24...Rc7  25.g4!  Having so much control of the game, White can easily afford to push the pawns in front of the king and launch a deadly attack.  25...Qc8  26.Kh1  Bf8  27.Rg1+-  g5 is coming and it's time for Black's king to write its own will. }
25. Rc3 Qc8 26. Nxb5
{ Strangely enough, we feel like this obvious capture complicates things a tiny bit.  26.g4  Qe8  27.Kh1+-  Rg1 and then g5 would have been a simple path to a win. }
26... Rxb5 27. h3 Qd7
{ 27...h5  Black is still objectively close to lost but their best shot is to push h5-h4 regardless. It may hinder White's breakthrough with g2-g4 a little. }
28. Qd2
{ Hikaru wishes to establish his queen on d4, which would eliminate any unpleasant surprises with Black's d5-d4 in the future. }
28... Qb7
{ 28...d4  Looks active but doesn't help Black  29.Rc4  White can timely capture the pawn on d4 and then infiltrate on the open d-file.  29...Rxb3  30.Rxd4  Qa7   30...Qc8  31.Qxa5  Rb5  32.Qa7+-  Black is clearly lost due to a lack of material and less active pieces.  31.Rd7  Rb7  32.Rxb7  Qxb7  33.Qxa5+-  With an extra pawn and exchange, White can confidently win after moving the queen out the pawn's way and gradually pushing a4-a5-a6 etc. }
29. Qe3 Qd7 30. Qd4 Qb7 31. Rb1 Qa7 32. b4 axb4 33. axb4
{ From this moment until the rest of the game, Nakamura's technique is impeccable. }
33... g6 34. Kh2 Kg7 35. Rcb3 Qb7 36. Qc3 Qb8 37. Kh1 Qb7 38. g4
{ Helps White to break with f5 in the future, if necessary. } 38... Qc8 39. Kg2
Kh7 40. Kf3 Qd7 41. Ke3
{ The king can run around like a dog on a grass lawn since Black is completely helpless. }
41... Bh4 42. Kd2 Be7 43. Kc2 Qc8 44. Ra1
{ Preparing to infiltrate on the open a-file. } 44... Qd7 45. Ra4 Rb7 46. Rba3
Bf8 47. Ra8 Bg7 48. R3a6 Rc7 49. h4 Qe7 50. g5
{ Completely destroys Black's hopes for even a slightest counterplay. } 50...
h5 51. Rb8 Qd7 52. Rbb6 Qc8 53. Kd3
{ The king now can move to d4, while the queen can help with invasion: Qa1-Ra8. }
53... d4 54. Qc2 Bf8 55. Qg2 Be7 56. Qa2 Qd7 57. Rb8 Rb7 58. Rxb7 Qxb7 59. Rb6
Qd7 60. Rb8 Bd8 61. Ra8 Bc7 62. Ra7 Kg7 63. Qc4 Qd8 64. Qxd4
{ The game is over. Nakamura had some fun moving the king around in the next stage of the game, probably to make a point of Black's lack of play. }
64... Qb8 65. Ra3 Bd8 66. Qc4 Qb7 67. Kc2 Be7 68. Rd3 Qa7 69. Kb2 Qb7 70. Qd4
Bf8 71. Qc4 Be7 72. Ra3 Qd7 73. Kc2 Bf8 74. Qd3 Qb7 75. Ra4 Be7 76. Kd1 Kf8 77.
Ke1 Kg7 78. Kf2 Kf8 79. Kg3 Kg7 80. Kf3 Kf8 81. Ke2 Kg7 82. Kd2 Kf8 83. Kc3 Kg7
84. Ra1 Kf8 85. Ra2 Kg7 86. Qa6 Qd7 87. Rd2 Qc7 88. Qa8
{ Now, it's truly the end since the queen is getting to e8 and then the rook moves to d7. }
88... Kh7 89. Kb3 Kg7 90. Kc2 Kh7 91. Qe8
{ Black can't defend f7 and against Rd7 at the same time. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "So, W. vs. Nakamura, H., Paris 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3
{ We reach the position in the game in our course after the following moves...  2.b3  Nf6  3.Bb2  e6  4.c4  c5  5.e3 }
2... Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5
{ The capture on d5 is almost mandatory. We can't let Black go d5-d4 and destroy our bishop on b2. }
6... exd5 7. Bb5
{ With the pawn being on e3 already, Bb5 is our preferred choice in all cases, except when Black's pawn is on a6 @@StartBracket@@of course@@EndBracket@@. Once the bishop pins the knight, we can trade later and worsen Black's pawn structure. }
7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4
{ An important move, aiming to create a weak isolated pawn in Black's position. }
9... Bg4
{ 9...cxd4  A better try for Black since the dark-squared bishop doesn't get distracted from the large diagonal b8-h2.  10.Nxd4  Bc7!  Getting ready for Qd6 if the need arises.  11.Nf3  Our knight needs to keep an eye on the h2.  11...a6  12.Bxc6  The only job for the bishop was to take the knight on c6, which we gladly do once prompted.  12...bxc6  13.Nbd2  Re8  14.Rc1  We will play against the c6-pawn. We may also push for Re1 and then e4 in the future. One thing that may hugely benefit us is the dark-squared bishop trade since it eliminates Black's chances for attack. }
10. dxc5
{ Distracts the bishop and temporarily creates an isolated pawn on d5. } 10...
Bxc5 11. h3
{ The bishop on g4 is really annoying, so we need to ask it to leave our premises. }
11... Bh5 12. Nc3 a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Rc1
{ As usual, the play is against the c6. } 14... Bd6 15. Ne2
{ A tough move to find. White voluntarily permits the trade on f3, not fearing the double pawns. Wesley So will utilize the open g-file to the fullest. }
15... Bxf3
{ 15...Rc8  16.Nf4!  Again, the best move is the one that creates double pawns! Black will have issues protecting c6 and a6.  16...Bxf4  17.exf4  Bxf3  18.Qxf3  Re8  19.Qd3  a5  20.Rc2⩲  White is comfortable, Rfc1 is coming. }
16. gxf3 Rc8 17. Qd3 Nd7 18. f4
{ Limits the scope of the bishop and mitigates the danger of ...Qg5 or ..Qh4. }
18... Re8 19. Ng3 Bf8
{ Loses a pawn and since then Black never quite recuperates.  19...Nc5  20.Qd4  Ne6  21.Qd1⩲  White is better still due to a simple plan: Qg4, and then Rc2-Rfc1. White attacks on both sides of the board. }
20. Qxa6 Nc5 21. Qe2 Ra8 22. Ba1 { Protects a2. } 22... Qd7
{ 22...Ne4  The best attempt is to trade the knights and try to survive in the endgame.  23.Nxe4  Rxe4  24.Rfd1±  White has a healthy extra pawn but it may take a long time to convert it into a win. }
23. Kh2 { Saves the pawn on h3 and prepares attack on the open g-file. } 23...
Ne6 24. Qg4 { We don't care about the a2 anymore, it's time for checkmate! }
24... Rxa2 25. Nh5 Kh8 26. Nf6
{ 26.Nxg7  Also wins in an elegant way.  26...Rxa1   26...Bxg7  27.Bxg7++-  27.Nxe8  Rxc1  28.Nf6+-  Qg8 and Nd7 are too powerful to deal with. }
26... Qd8 27. Qf5 g6
{ If they take the knight, we go Bf6 and win the queen on d8. } 28. Nxe8+ Rxa1
29. Qxf7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nakamura, H. vs. So, W., Abidjan 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3
{ We transpose to the position in the game in our course after the following moves...  2.b3  Nf6  3.Bb2  e6  4.c4  Be7  5.e3 }
2... Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 Be7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3
{ We can decide later what to do with the bishop on f1. Meanwhile, we can pressure Black's pawn on d5 with a natural-looking Nc3. }
6... c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ 7...exd5  Works out better for White since we would still have our knight on c3 attacking a pawn on d5 @@StartBracket@@which would be an isolated pawn after we take on c5 later@@EndBracket@@.  8.d4  Nc6  9.Be2  Ne4  10.O-O  ⩲  We are ready to capture on c5 and then pile up on the d5. }
8. Nxd5
{ 8.Be2  We discovered this interesting approach almost last minute before the course went live.  8...Nc6  9.Qc2  We don't show our cards just yet and prepare for something a little unusual.  9...Ncb4  10.Qb1  b6  11.h4!?  That's the idea behind Qc2. We would like to jump Ng5 and launch a quick attack. This approach may best work in the shorter time controls when your opponents don't have enough time to deal with an aggressive attack. }
8... exd5 9. d4 { Emphasizing how weak the pawn on d5 is. } 9... Nc6 10. Be2
cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qa5+
{ Black needs to deprive us of castling rights; otherwise, they just suffer with weakness on d5 for nothing. }
12. Kf1 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bf5 14. Bd3
{ 14.h4  We like this approach the best. The point is to push h5-h6 if possible and do a rook lift later - Rh3-g3 @@StartBracket@@obviously, after we trade the light-squared bishops@@EndBracket@@.  14...Rac8  15.Bd3  Be4  16.h5  h6  Allowing h6 would have an utter disaster for Black since the likelihood of a checkmate on a1-h8 diagonal is high in that case.  17.Rh3  White has an easy game, Rg3 is coming next. }
14... Be4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qg4 Bf6
{ Wesley So sacrifices a pawn, betting on his piece activity.  16...Qa6+  Black can save the pawn and go into an almost equal endgame.  17.Kg1  Qg6  18.Qxg6  hxg6  19.g3  White has a microscopic edge here but, with the correct play, Black should hold relatively easily. Nonetheless, White is risk-free here. The plan would involve Kg2, Rac1, Rhd1 and the play on the queenside. }
17. Qxe4 Qa6+ 18. Kg1 Rfe8 19. Qf4 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Rad8 21. Qb2 Rd5
{ 21...Qa5  A second alternative for Black.  22.b4  Qc7  23.g3  It might be an uphill battle for White trying to convert an extra pawn. Our best shot is to play h4, Kh2, and connect the rooks on d1 and c1. }
22. h4
{ A great idea, preparing a rook lift. This is the fastest way for White to develop the kingside. }
22... Red8 23. Rh3 Rd2 24. Qe5 R2d5
{ 24...Rxa2  Black should have taken the pawn, no matter how risky it looked.  25.Rxa2  Qxa2  26.Qe7   26.Rg3  Somehow, we don't have more than a draw in the following lines.  26...g6  27.h5  Rd1+  28.Kh2  Qxf2  29.Qb8+  Kg7  30.h6+  Typically, such moves win the game. In this case, we can only achieve a draw since Black also has a decent attack on our king.  30...Kxh6  31.Rh3+  Kg5  32.Qe5+  f5  33.Rg3+  Kh5  34.Rh3+=  26...Qd2  27.Qxb7  Qe1+  28.Kh2  Qxf2  29.Qxa7  We need to grab as many pawns as we can before Black catches up and protects the back rank with h6 or h5.  29...h5  30.Qe7  Rd2  31.Rg3  White has some practical chances for winning. Just make sure not to play Stockfish here since it will always make a draw with 100% accuracy. }
25. Qf4
{ Black is in trouble now since White has managed to develop successfully and has a healthy extra pawn. }
25... h5 26. Rf3 Qe6 27. Rc1 Rd1+ 28. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 29. Kh2 Rd2
{ A blunder, costing Black a game immediately.  29...Qd6  The best shot was going into a bleak rook endgame down a pawn.  30.Qxd6  Rxd6  31.Rf5  g6  32.Rb5± }
30. Qb8+ Kh7 31. Qxb7
{ White picks up a lot of pawns and wins easily from here. } 31... f6 32. Qxa7
Qe5+ 33. Rg3 f5 34. f4 Qa1 35. Qf7 Rd1 36. Qxf5+ Kg8 37. Qe6+ Kh7 38. Qg6+ Kg8
39. Qe8+ Kh7 40. Qxh5+ Kg8 41. Rf3 { Avoiding a checkmate on h1. } 41... Rh1+
42. Kg3 Qe1+ 43. Kg4 { White is 'only' up 5 pawns! } 43... Qe2 44. g3 Rf1 45.
Qd5+ Kh7 46. b4 Rg1 47. b5 { The king on g4 is the safest it has ever been. }
47... Qg2 48. b6 Rh1 49. b7
{ The check on h3 doesn't help since we can bravely go Kg5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Aronian, L. vs. Vachier Lagrave, M., Leuven 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4
{ We reach the position in the game in our course after the following moves...  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  b6  5.Bg2  Bb7  6.O-O  O-O  7.c4  c5  8.d4 }
2... c5 3. g3 g6 4. b3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Bg7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. Qxd4
Nc6
{ Another way to develop the knight is to d7.  9...d6  10.Nc3  Nbd7  11.Ne1  We like the trade of the bishop since the majority of the pawns in the Maroczy bind pawn structures are on the light squares, and traditionally the light-squared bishop is somewhat limited in scope. Here, we can now safely play e4, f3, g4 @@StartBracket@@later, once it's not a blunder@@EndBracket@@ and there will be no bishop on g2 to complain about such arrangement.  11...Bxg2  12.Nxg2  Rc8  13.Rfd1⩲  White is better since Black struggles to reclaim the space without the typical breaks like b5 or d5. }
10. Qc3 Rc8 11. Rd1 { Prevents d5 and opens the retreat square for the queen. }
11... Qc7 12. Qe1
{ If the rook was still on f1, the queen on e1 would block it unnecessarily. We are now ready to develop like this: Nc3 and then either e4 or Rac1. }
12... Qb8 13. Nc3 Rfd8 14. Rac1
{ 14.e4!  It was more productive to conquer the center right away.  14...e6  15.Rd2  d6  16.Rad1±  Black lacks any counterplay and we have an easy target on d6. }
14... e6 15. Ng5 h6 16. Nge4 Nxe4
{ 16...Ne8!  A much better move, emphasizing how uncoordinated the knights are on c3 and e4, fighting for the same squares. }
17. Bxe4 Ne7
{ An almost decisive mistake.  17...Ne5  The knights are best placed in the middle.  18.Bxb7  Qxb7  19.Qd2⩲  White still maintains some edge. Our plan could involve h3, Kh2, and then f4, attacking the knight and gaining a lot of space on the kingside. }
18. Ba3 { White wins at least a pawn. } 18... Nf5
{ 18...d6  The most resilient.  19.Bxb7  Qxb7  20.Nb5+-  Wins the d6 pawn or an exchange if Black chooses to go d5 and still allow Nd6.   20.Bxd6  Also works, but Black has a bit more play here than after 20.Nb5.  20...Nf5  21.Ba3  Nd4  22.Bb2± }
19. Bxf5 gxf5 20. Be7 { The winning move! } 20... Re8 21. Bd6 Qa8 22. Nb5
{ Wins an exchange and the game. } 22... Ba6 23. Nc7 Rxc7 24. Bxc7 Qc6
{ 24...d5  MVL should have chosen this line, giving him better chances for survival.  25.Qb4  d4  26.Qa4  Bb7  27.c5+-  White still wins but at least Black has a visually pleasing pawn on d4. }
25. Bd6 Bb7 26. f3
{ Effectively stopping all malicious activity on h1-a8 diagonal. } 26... e5 27.
Qd2 e4 28. Qd5
{ Follows the best practices - trade queens if you're up in material.  28.f4  Looks easier since we want to keep the game closed when our opponent has two bishops.  28...e3  29.Qd5+- }
28... Qc8 29. Qxf5 exf3 30. exf3 Re2 31. Qd3 Qe8 32. Bf4 Qe7 33. Rf1
{ Aronian now has to be precise. He still keeps everything under control though, and doesn't let his winning advantage slip away. }
33... Qc5+ 34. Kh1 Rxa2 35. Rce1 Qh5 36. Re2
{ The rook trade is welcome since it makes our king way safer. } 36... Rxe2 37.
Qxe2 Bc6 38. Kg2 b5 39. cxb5 Bxb5 40. Qe8+ Kh7 41. Rc1 Qd5 42. Qe4+
{ Finally, the endgame! One of the best feelings in a chess game is to play for two results only - either you win or it's a draw. }
42... Qxe4 43. fxe4 Bc6 44. Rc4 Kg6 45. g4 { Stops f5. } 45... h5 46. g5 a6 47.
Kf3 f6 48. gxf6 Bxf6 49. Rc2
{ White's dream is to trade the bishops and easily win rook vs. bishop endgame. }
49... Kf7 50. Ke3 Bd8 51. Kd4 Ke6 52. Rg2 Bf6+ 53. Kd3 d5 54. e5 Bb5+
{ 54...Bxe5  fails quickly  55.Bxe5  Kxe5  56.Rg5+  Kf4  57.Rxh5 } 55. Kc3 Bh4
56. Rg7
{ Misses a chance to finish the game way faster. This move prolongs the game by 30 moves or so.   56.Bg5  Be1+  57.Bd2  Bh4  58.Kd4  Rg6 is coming and White wins super easily after picking up the pawn on d5. }
56... Bf2 57. Rg5 h4 58. Kd2 Bc5 59. Rg6+ Kf5 60. Rf6+ Ke4 61. e6 d4 62. Bh6
Be7 63. Rf7 Bb4+ 64. Kd1 Ke5 65. e7 Ke6 66. Rf4 Bxe7 67. Rxd4 Bf6 68. Rd2 Be5
69. Rf2 Bc6
{ 69...Kd5  More resilient.  70.Bf4  Bd4  71.Rg2  White still has a good chance for winning but it may take forever. }
70. Bf4 Bd4 71. Rd2 Bc5 72. Rc2 Kd5 73. Ke2 Bd7 74. Rd2+ Kc6 75. Kf3 Be6 76.
Rd3 Kb5 77. Ke4 h3
{ One more mistake, and this time Aronian takes advantage of it.   77...Bb6  78.Ke5  Bg4  79.Kd6  White plans to go Be3 next, hopefully trading the bishops or at least squeezing the king out to the a-file eventually. }
78. Ke5 Bg4 79. Rg3 Bd7 80. Be3 Ba3 81. Bd2 Bc5 82. Rg5 Kc6 83. Rg6+ Kb5 84.
Rh6 Bb6 85. Kd6 Bg4 86. Rh4 Bc5+ 87. Kc7 Be6
{ Final blunder.   87...Bb6+  88.Kd6  Bc5+  89.Ke5  Bc8  White still needs another 30-40 moves to win this. Unfortunately, we can't use the tablebases to know the precise result of this endgame @@StartBracket@@since the tablebases are only valid for 7 pieces remaining or less@@EndBracket@@. We would estimate White's winning chances here as slightly over 70%. }
88. Rh5
{ White wins the bishop after b4 or Be3 on the next move, so Black resigned. }
*

