[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jumabayev, R. vs. Yakubboev, N., Tashkent 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game, we will look into Chigorin Defense. We covered it in Part 7. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 3. Nf3
{ In our course, we get here after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  Nc6  2.d4  d5  3.c4  . }
3... Bg4 4. cxd5 Bxf3 5. gxf3
{ We can't be bothered by the double pawns on f2 and f3 since they, in fact, help us control more space in the center. In addition, the g-file can be used later for an attack. }
5... Qxd5 6. e3 e5 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qd6 10. Rb1 Rb8
{ 10...b6  11.f4  exf4  12.e4  A typical pawn sacrifice, used to strengthen our center.  12...Nge7  13.Qf3±  The f4 is falling soon. }
11. Rg1 g6 12. f4 exf4 13. e4
{ We sacrifice to undouble our pawns and eliminate Black's pawn on e5, which was the only one putting pressure on our center. }
13... Nf6 14. e5
{ 14.Qf3  We think this move might be an easier one to play. Keep the pawns on d4 and e4 for a while. We would like to reach a stable position where our king is safer on f1, for example, and only then proceed to gain the new ground.  14...O-O  15.Bd3  Nd7  16.Bxf4±  We should hide the king on f1 next, and go e5 soon. }
14... Qe6 15. Bg2
{ A serious inaccuracy, giving away the advantage.  15.Bxf4  O-O  16.Rg3±  Prepares Bh3 and protects the king - for example: if Ne4 then Re3! }
15... Nd5 { White really struggles to get the f4 back. } 16. Rb5 Nce7 17. Qb3
c6
{ Removing the knight from d5 wasn't an option since it would give away the f4. }
18. Rxb7 Rxb7 19. Qxb7 O-O 20. c4
{ White correctly estimates that it's now or never moment. Attack the knight or else Black will start their own attack with c5 or f6. }
20... Nb6 21. Bb4 Nd7 22. Bxe7
{ A blunder, which objectively leads to a lost position for White.  22.Bd6  White could have challenged Black quite a bit.  22...Qxc4  The best way for Black to escape trouble.  23.Qxd7  Qc3+  24.Ke2  Nf5  25.Qxf5!  Otherwise, Black may have a real attack with the queen + knight combo.  25...gxf5  26.Bf3+  Kh8  27.Bxf8  Qc4+  We didn't believe it at first, but Black can actually pull off a survival here.  28.Ke1  Qc1+  29.Bd1  Qc3+  30.Kf1  Qh3+  31.Ke2  f3+  32.Ke1  Qg2!!  The only move!  33.Rf1  We can't take the queen since the pawn on g2 will promote into a new queen.  33...Qg5  34.Bxf3  Qc1+  35.Ke2  Qc4+  36.Ke1=  Okay, Black worked extra hard, so we can call it a draw. }
22... Rb8 23. Qxc6 Qxe7 24. Be4 Rb2 25. e6 Nf6
{ A natural move, nonetheless dropping a ton of advantage.  25...Nf8!  The main merit of the knight on f8 - it doesn't block the queen's path to h4.  26.exf7+  Kg7  27.Kf1  Qh4  28.Rg2  Qh5!  The queen is on the rampage! Again, the only winning move.  29.Bf3  Rb1+  30.Ke2  Qa5-+  Qe1, Qa2, Re1 - too many threats to deal with, so White is lost. }
26. Kf1 Kg7 27. Bf3
{ Jumabayev gets his thoughts in order and starts playing extraordinarily strong defensive moves. The king's situation is fixed, and the bishop is untouchable on f3 - a vast improvement achieved within the two moves. }
27... Rb6 28. Qc5
{ 28.Qc8  Also works well  28...Rxe6  29.Qb8  After hitting the pawn of f4, White should achieve a draw easily. }
28... Qxe6 29. Kg2 Rb2 30. Qa3 Rc2
{ Since here, White is out of the danger zone.  30...Rd2  Would have made White sweat much more for a draw.  31.Rd1  Rxd1  32.Bxd1  Qe4+  33.Bf3  Qxd4  34.Qe7!  Most likely, White should be able to make a draw here since all of our pieces are active and there are not that many pieces left on the board. }
31. Rc1 Rxc4 32. Rxc4 Qxc4 33. Qxa7
{ Now, Black has to be the one making a draw. Otherwise, we push the a-pawn all the way to a8. }
33... Qc2 34. a4 h5 35. h3 Ne4 36. d5 Qd3 37. Qe7 Nd2 38. Qe5+ Kg8 39. Qe8+ Kg7
40. Qe5+ Kf8 41. Qe2 Nxf3 42. Qxf3 Qc4 43. a5 Ke8 44. h4 Kd7 45. Kg1 Qa4 46.
Qc3 { An interesting attempt in objectively equal endgame. } 46... Qd1+ 47. Kh2
Qxd5 48. a6 Qa2
{ 48...f3  leads to a draw.  49.Qf6  Kc8  50.Qh8+  Kc7  51.Qf6=  Nobody can make considerable progress here, so a draw is the most likely result. }
49. Qd4+ Kc6 50. Qe4+
{ White should be winning now since the a-pawn is likely to promote. } 50...
Kc5 51. Qe7+ Kd4 { 51...Kb6  52.Qb7+  Kc5  53.Kg2+- } 52. Qd6+ Ke4 53. Kg2
{ An unexpected slip.  53.Qb6!  Ke5  54.a7+-  White promotes the pawn shortly. }
53... Qa4 54. Qb6 Qd1
{ Misses a chance to make a draw.  54...f3+  55.Kg3  Kd3!  The king has to get away from checks on b7 and enable Black's queen attack on g4.  56.Qe3+  Kc2  57.Qxf3  Qxa6  58.Qxf7  Kd2=  As long as Black doesn't trade into a lost pawn endgame, they should be okay here. }
55. Qb7+ Ke5 56. Qe7+ Kf5 57. Qxf7+ Kg4 58. Qxg6+ Kxh4 59. Qf6+ Kg4 60. Qg6+
Kh4 61. Qf5
{ Misses a stalemate trick and complicates White's win by tenfold.   61.a7  Qd5+  62.Kh2  Qa2  63.Qf6+  Kg4  64.Qg7+  Kh4   64...Kf3  65.Qg2+  65.Qd4  Kg4  66.Qd7+  It's a checkmate in 15 or something moves, according to Stockfish. Hard to argue with such evaluation! :@@EndBracket@@  66...Kh4  67.Qd8+  Kg4  68.a8=Q  Qxf2+  69.Qg2+  Reaching the end, finally.  69...Qxg2+  70.Kxg2  The queen will collect the pawns soon and win easily. }
61... Qf3+ 62. Kg1 Qd1+ 63. Kh2 Qf3
{ 63...Qd4!  Still makes it hard to win @@StartBracket@@but still winning for White@@EndBracket@@. }
64. Qf6+ Kg4 65. Qe6+ Kh4 66. Qe7+ Kg4 67. Qb7 Qh3+ { 67...Qxf2+  68.Qg2++- }
68. Kg1 Qd3 69. a7 Qd1+ 70. Kh2 Qd6 71. Qg2+
{ No more tricks, White promotes the a-pawn next. } *

