[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 O-O 6. b3 c5 7. Bb2 b6 8. Nc3
Bb7 9. e3 dxc4 10. bxc4 Nc6 11. Qe2
{ We arrive at this position via a different move order in Chapter 1.1. } 11...
Qc7 12. Nb5
{ Makes Black waste a tempo and eventually provokes a6, which weakens the pawn on b6. }
12... Qd7 13. Rfd1 a6 14. Nc3
{ Now, the pawn on b6 is weak and can sometimes become a target. } 14... Qc7
15. Rac1 Rfd8 16. Ba1
{ The bishop is placed on a1 the best since it's out of Black's reach and still attacks on a1-h8 diagonal. }
16... Rab8 17. Na4
{ 17.h4  We like keeping things vague! h4 may help us later if we get a chance to play h5-h6. Meanwhile, let's wait and see if we can push d4 soon. }
17... Ba8
{ 17...Na5  A better try, putting some pressure on c4.  18.d4  cxd4  19.exd4  Our plan here is to push d5 at some point, opening all files and diagonals for the attack. }
18. d4 Qa7 19. Ng5
{ A great idea, opening up the bishop on g2 and preparing d5. } 19... h6 20.
Ne4 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Na5
{ Almost loses the game since White's attack after d5 can't be stopped.   21...cxd4  22.exd4  Bf6  Black can only save the game if they trade a lot of pieces, especially the ultra-dangerous bishop on a1.  23.d5  Bxa1  24.Rxa1  exd5  25.cxd5  Ne5  26.Bg2⩲  White is still in control due to a passed pawn on d5. We would want to bring the rook from a1 to c1 and prepare d6. }
22. d5 b5 23. cxb5 axb5 24. Qg4
{ The queen has been sitting on e2 for way too long and now effectively shakes off some dust from itself by attacking the g7. }
24... Bf8 25. Nxc5 f5
{ Taking the knight wasn't possible because of the checkmate on g7. } 26. Qg6
fxe4
{ Loses on the spot.  26...Bxc5  27.Rxc5!  27...fxe4  28.Be5!  Hitting b8 and threatening Rc7.  28...Qf7   28...Rb7  29.Bd4!!  Getting ready for a discovered attack - Rc8.  29...Qb8  30.dxe6  Rf8  31.Bxg7!!  A beautiful finish. We must say, the bishop dies a hero!  31...Rxg7  32.Qxh6  Rh5 is a giant threat.  32...Rh7  33.Qg5+  Rg7  34.Qh4+-  Rh5 is coming and Black is helpless. Like, +8 for White, according to Stockfish.  29.Qxf7+  Kxf7  30.Bxb8  Rxb8  31.Rc7+  Kf6  32.dxe6  Nc6  33.Rdd7±  We have no doubt White would have won this endgame since the minor pieces fail to match with the well-coordinated rooks on the 7th rank. }
27. Nxe4 Ba3 28. Nf6+
{ The checkmate now is just a matter of time. Notice that Black's pieces are crowded on the queenside, which is certainly not helping the Black king. }
28... Kf8 29. dxe6 Qb7 { 29...Bxc1  30.Nd7++- } 30. e4
{ Never too late to lose - checkmate on h1 or g2 should be stopped. } 30...
gxf6 31. Qxf6+ Ke8 32. Qg6+ Kf8 33. Qxh6+ Ke8 34. Qh5+
{ Black resigned due to checkmate in a few moves.  34.Qh5+  Kf8  35.Qh8+  Ke7  36.Qg7+  Ke8  37.Qg8+  Bf8  38.Qg6+  Ke7  39.Qf7 }
*

