[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Svidler, P. vs. Kokarev, D., Riyadh 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3
{ 2.b3  We get to the position in the game after 6 moves after the following move order in the course.  2...g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  O-O  5.Bg2  c5  6.c4 }
2... g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. Bg2 c5
{ In our course, we examine in a great detail 5...c5, 5...d5, and 5...d6. } 6.
c4 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. d4
{ The only reasonable attempt for gaining an edge. If we push the pawn to d3 instead, Black can easily equalize the game with e5, neutralizing the bishop on b2. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Nc3 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc6 12. Qd3
{ 12.Qd2  is not as good since the queen on d2 fails to support e2-e4 push. }
12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qa5 14. Rac1
{ Most of the time, the rooks are best placed on c1 and d1 - the main events will be held on the queenside and the c- and d- files have the highest propensity for getting open. }
14... a6 15. a4
{ Remember to play this move whenever Black attempts a queenside attack with b5. }
15... Rac8 16. e4
{ Further cements White's advantage in space. Notice how now majority of White's pawns are on the light squares, which helps our bishop on b2 being super active - nobody's in the way! }
16... Qb4 17. Na2
{ As soon as they cross the middle line, hit them immediately before they become dangerous. }
17... Qa5 18. Bc3 Qc5 19. Nb4
{ 19.Rfd1  was a little easier if White didn't want to engage in a tactical battle. }
19... Nxe4 20. Qxe4
{ 20.Nd5!  White missed a chance to hit the e7 right away.  20...Nxc3  21.Nxe7+  Kh8  22.Rxc3!  One less intruder in our camp!  22...Rce8  23.Nd5±  White has a stable advantage due to a beautiful outpost for the knight on d5. The rook on c3 is untouchable as will be shown in the next few moves.  23...Bxc3  24.Qxc3+  f6  25.Nxf6  Qe5  26.Qxe5  Rxe5  27.Nd7+-  The key fork, leading to a winning rook endgame. }
20... Bxc3 21. Nd5 Bf6 22. Nxf6+
{ 22.b4  White had an option for playing for an attack, by keeping the knight on d5 and pushing h4-h5.  22...Qa7  23.h4!  We like White's chances here. Black has no active counterplay against a fairly straightforward plan - h5 and Rh1. }
22... exf6 23. Qxb7 Rb8 24. Qf3 Rb6
{ A passive move, helping White to bring the rooks to the perfect positions.   24...Rfe8!  Perhaps, you would be surprised to learn that Stockfish evaluates this position as equal. We still think that in a real human game White maintains a slight initiative.  25.Rcd1  Kg7  26.Rd5  Qb6  27.Rb1  Re6  28.h4  White looks a bit more active, having a potential for a pawn majority attack on the queenside. Still, Black can hold with h5 on the next move. }
25. Rfd1 f5 26. Rd5 Qa3 27. Rc3 Rfb8
{ 27...Re8  with the idea of playing Re6 on the next move would have been a better defense. }
28. Rdd3 Qc5 29. Re3 h5 30. h4 Qa3 31. Rcd3
{ White plays a waiting game so far, hoping to invade on the 7th rank and attack the king. }
31... Kg7 32. Qf4 Kg8 33. Re7 R6b7
{ 33...Qc5  was still holding for some time but White has an undeniable advantage due to a better pawn structure and more active pieces. }
34. Rxb7 Rxb7 35. Rxd6 Qxb3 36. Rd8+
{ Finally getting on a date with the Black's king. } 36... Kg7
{ 36...Kh7  37.Qe5  Wins easily as well. } 37. Qe5+
{ Qe8 is coming and Black has no defense against White's multiple threats. } *

