[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kramnik, V. vs. Demchenko, A., Tbilisi 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. Bg2
{ We arrive at this position in Part 1 after a slightly different move order. We go 2. b3, 3. Bb2, and then 4.g 3. }
5... d6 6. d4 Nbd7 7. O-O Re8 8. a4
{ A surprisingly useful move, aiming to gain more ground on the queenside. }
8... Rb8
{ 8...a5  9.Na3  The knight is going to c4, helping to fight against Black's pawn push e7-e5. We can also bring the rook to e1 to support e2-e4. }
9. c4 e5 10. dxe5 Ng4
{ 10...dxe5  loses a pawn  11.Nxe5!  Nc5   11...Nxe5  12.Qxd8  Rxd8   12...Nf3+  13.Bxf3  Rxd8  14.a5±  We should aim for Na3 @@StartBracket@@Nc3 blocks the bishop on b2@@EndBracket@@ and then Rad1.  13.Bxe5±  We will trade the bishops after Ne8, and then should proceed with Nc3 and Rad1. The endgame looks almost winning for White - an extra pawn, no counterplay for Black, and an easy expansion plan on the queenside @@StartBracket@@a5, b4 etc.@@EndBracket@@.  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.b4⩲  White is better. Black still has some play, so we need to play carefully for the next few moves before we can call it a stable advantage. We would recommend trading a few pieces to make things less sharp. }
11. a5
{ 11.Qc2  Looks promising to protect the bishop and force Black to show their true intensions regarding our pawn on e5.  11...Ngxe5  12.Nxe5  Nxe5  13.Nc3⩲  White has an easy play - Nd5, e4, f4. We can bring the rook from a1 to d1 or e1, depending on Black's moves and one's personal taste. }
11... dxe5 12. h3 Nh6 13. e4 f6
{ Fails to bring the knight to e6, from where it can land on d4, messing with White's plans.   13...Nc5  14.Nbd2  f6  15.b4  The game is simple for White - just push the pawn on the queenside and attack there. The king on g8 is not our primary target since it has lots of defenders around it.  15...Ne6  16.c5⩲  The plan is to play Qb3, Nc4, Rad1. Since Black can't respond with the same level of activity on the opposite side, White maintains a comfortable edge. }
14. b4
{ White controls the majority of the queenside, and Black may be running out of space for their pieces soon. }
14... Nf8 15. Nc3 Be6 16. Qe2 Qc8 17. Kh2
{ We can simply protect the pawn. Pushing the pawn to h4 would help Black to establish the knight on g4. }
17... Nf7 18. Rfd1 c6 19. Bc1
{ A clever maneuver, aiming to reposition the bishop to e3. From there, it will be effectively targeting the pawn on a7 and the whole queenside. }
19... f5 20. Be3 b6 21. axb6 axb6 22. Rac1 Qc7 23. Nd5
{ White's pieces are placed perfectly, so it's time to look for a tactical blow. }
23... cxd5
{ 23...Qb7  doesn't help much either, but still technically more resilient than a capture on d5.  24.Nxb6  f4  25.Bc5±  The plan: trade the bishop on f8 and push c5, permanently establishing control over Black's queenside due to the knight's invincibility on b6. }
24. cxd5 Qe7 25. dxe6 Nxe6 26. exf5
{ The trade on f5 weakens Black's pawns and opens up the diagonal for the bishop on g2. }
26... gxf5 27. Qb5
{ The queen sends a memo to everybody that the pawn on b6 is going to fall soon. }
27... f4
{ 27...Nd6  White dominates in every line as can be seen in the following lines.  28.Qc6  Ne4   28...Red8  29.Bxb6   28...Nf7  29.Nh4  29.Nh4  Black has way too many weaknesses and a weak king. In particular, the f5 pawn falls right away. }
28. gxf4 exf4 29. Rd7 Qf6 30. Bd2
{ The material is even. Everything is okay for Black, right? Not quite. Stockfish shows a generous +3 for White, which means Black defenses are falling soon after Rc6 and Bc3, among many other attacking moves White can play. }
30... Rbc8 31. Rxc8 Rxc8 32. Qxb6
{ The rest is a matter of a simple technique. } 32... Rc2 33. Qb7 Bf8 34. Qe4
Qg6 35. Qd5 { A queen trade after Nh4 was also winning for White. } 35... Qf6
36. h4 { Perhaps, Bf1-c4 was a slightly more precise idea. } 36... Bg7 37. Bh3
Nf8 38. Rb7 h6 39. Bg4 Rb2 40. Bh5 Ng6 41. Bxg6 Qxg6 42. Rb8+ Bf8
{ 42...Kh7  43.h5  Finishes the game instantly. } 43. Ne5 Rxd2 44. Rxf8+
{ 44.Nxg6  also wins but in a less fancy way.  44...Rxd5  45.Ne7+  Kg7  46.Nxd5 }
