1. e4
{ You may be wondering why would we include 1. e4 game in the repertoire on 1. Nf3? The reason is simple: we believe the knowledge of a certain pawn structure arising after move 12 will be beneficial to you as a chess player and is relevant to playing this repertoire better. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 a6 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O
d6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Na4 Rb8 11. c4 c5 12. b3
{ This pawn structure is mentioned in Part 3. } 12... Be7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Qe1
{ 14.f4  The immediate f4 was also possible. So, just in case, you get into a similar situation and forget about Qe1, don't worry. As they say, many roads lead to Rome here. }
14... Nd7 15. Rd1 Bb7
{ 15...Ne5  Perhaps, Black should have tried putting the knight on c6, from where it annoys White by eyeing the square on d4.  16.Qd2  Nc6  17.f4  Our plan is simple: advance on the kingside with g4, g5, f5. Remember that you can also do a deadly rook lift - Rf1-f3-h3, and target h7. }
16. Qc3 Bf6 17. Qd2 Be7 18. Qc3 Bf6 19. Qd2
{ Magnus just teases his opponent. We are willing to bet everything we have that he never thought about a draw for a second. He must have repeated the moves just to gain some additional time on his clock since almost all serious classical tournaments have an increment after each move. }
19... Be7 20. f4 { Vamos! The pawns are ready to party on the kingside. } 20...
e5 21. Bc3
{ A brilliant idea to bring the bishop to a5 and freeze Black's queenside. }
21... Bc6 22. Ba5 Qb7 23. Nc3
{ You may notice that now Black doesn't have a standard idea on the queenside - a6-a5-a4 and attack on the b-file. }
23... exf4
{ 23...h6  is better according to the engines but we hardly believe Black can survive. }
24. gxf4 Rfe8 25. e5
{ One of the coolest pawn sacrifices we have witnessed in modern practice. White wants to block the e-file, which limits Black's play tremendously and gives White a green light to attack on the kingside for free. }
25... Bxg2 26. Qxg2 dxe5
{ 26...Qxg2+  27.Kxg2+-  White wins the pawn on d6 and, shortly, the game. }
27. Nd5 { Threatens Nc7 among many other things. } 27... e4 28. Bc3 f6 29. Kh1
{ The open file must be used, so Carlsen prepares Rg1. } 29... Kh8 30. Rg1 Bf8
31. Ne3
{ Looks like this retreat may signal an admission of a defeat, but that's not quite the case... }
31... Qc6 { 31...Nb6  doesn't work since White wins a pawn  32.Bxf6+- } 32. Rd5
{ The point of Ne3! The rook is going to h5, and White's attack is in a full swing. }
32... Qe6 33. Rh5 Qf7 34. Qh3
{ We can now fully appreciate a pawn sacrifice earlier on move 25. The pawn on e4 deprives Black of counterplay on the e-file and the rook on e8 looks helpless. }
34... g6 35. Rh4 Rb6 36. f5
{ The rest is easy. All of White's pieces are in attack and the pawn on f5 adds a final touch by opening the files. }
36... Ne5 37. Nd5 Rd6 38. fxg6 Nxg6 39. Bxf6+ { 39.Nxf6  Also wins. } 39...
Rxf6 40. Rxh7+
{ If they go Qh7, we trade queens, and then recapture on f6 with a check and a fork. }
*

