1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3
{ 2.b3  We transpose to the position in the game after the following moves...  2...g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  O-O  5.Bg2  c5  6.c4  Nc6  7.O-O  d6  8.d4 }
2... c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. c4 g6 5. b3 Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O d6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4
Bd7 10. Nc2
{ An interesting idea of not allowing Black to trade the knights on d4, which makes some sense since you generally don't want to trade if you have more space. }
10... Qa5
{ 10...Qc8  Black can also try trading the bishop with Bh3. We have noticed that this idea is especially popular in the online games. People wrongfully assume that the lack of the bishop on g2 is going to make White's king weaker. This is not the case if you manage to go f3 and e4 in most situations, building an impenetrable fortress for the king.  11.Nc3  Bh3  12.f3  We will push e4 on the next move, followed by Qd2, Rad1, Ne3, aiming for d5. }
11. Nc3 Rfc8 12. Rc1 Rab8 13. Ne3 { The knights are ready to jump on d5. }
13... a6 14. a4 { As usual, we have to stop b5 no matter what. } 14... Qh5 15.
Qd2 Bh6
{ 15...Bh3  16.Bxh3  We can get rid of Black's bishop right away. The more we trade, the less attacking chances Black will have.  16...Qxh3  17.Ncd5  Trading the knight on f6, so it can never go to g4.  17...Nxd5  18.Nxd5⩲  White has more space and should continue with f4 and e4 once the time is right. }
16. Ncd5 Nxd5
{ 16...Ng4  Looks dangerous but White has a simple remedy.  17.h4  No point in putting the pawn on h3 because Black can win it with the bishop on d7 by trading on e3 first.  17...Nxe3  18.fxe3!?  A peculiar capture, hugely favored by Stockfish over a more down-to-earth Ne3. The point is to open up the f-file for the attacking purposes and keep the knight on d5 for as long as possible.  18...Bg7  19.Bxg7  Kxg7  20.b4±  White has a serious edge due to attack on the f-file and a threat of b5 to win the pawn on e7. }
17. cxd5 Ne5 18. f4 Ng4 19. Nxg4
{ 19.h3!  White missed a chance to get a huge advantage.  19...Nxe3  20.Qd4!  An in-between move, probably missed by White.   20.Qxe3  Bxh3  21.Qxe7  Bg7  leads to a fine game for Black.  20...f6  21.Qxe3  Kf7   21...Bxh3  22.Qxe7  Bg7  23.Rxc8+  Rxc8  24.Rf3+-  The point is to play Rc3! Then, if Black goes Rf8, we can win after Rc7.  22.g4  Qh4  23.Bc3±  Black lacks space and the threat of Be1 is hard to deal with, to say the least. }
19... Bxg4 20. Qd4 f6 21. e3
{ 21.Kf2⩲  White is still a bit better here due to more space and the fact that the pawn on e2 is untouchable.  21...Bxe2?  22.Rfe1+- }
21... Bh3
{ 21...Rxc1  was the easiest way to get to an equal game.  22.Rxc1  Rc8= } 22.
Bxh3 Qxh3 23. Qe4 Kf7
{ 23...Kf8  looks a bit better in case White wants to play f5. The king will be further away from a check on e6. }
24. Bd4 Qd7 { 24...Qg4  Blocks White from playing f5. } 25. Bb6
{ 25.Rxc8  White missed a chance to push f5 and attack the king.  25...Rxc8  26.f5± }
25... f5 26. Qd3 Bg7
{ The game is about equal now. Black doesn't have any considerable weaknesses, so White's advantage in space can fizzle out really qucikly once the multiple trades occur. }
27. Kg2 Bf6 28. Kf3 { Attempting to push h3 and g4. } 28... h5 29. h3 Bb2 30.
Rc2 Bf6 31. Rfc1 Rxc2 32. Qxc2 g5
{ The game will soon enter a rook endgame stage, which is fairly equal until move  54. If you're not a big fan of an endgame part, feel free to skip the next 22 moves and go directly there.32...h4  Would have given Black a good counterplay on the kingside. }
33. fxg5 Bxg5 34. Qc7 Qxc7 35. Rxc7 Bf6 36. Ba7 Rg8 37. Bd4 h4 38. gxh4 Bxd4
39. exd4 b5 40. axb5 axb5 41. Rb7 Rg1 42. Rxb5 Rd1 43. Ke3 Rh1 44. Kf4 Kf6 45.
Rb8 Rf1+ 46. Ke3 Re1+ 47. Kf3 Rf1+ 48. Ke3 Re1+ 49. Kf3 Re4 50. Rf8+ Kg6 51.
h5+ Kg5 52. h6 Rh4 53. Kg3 f4+ 54. Kg2 Kg6
{ A decisive blunder.  54...Rxh6  55.b4  e5!  The only move to stay in the game! Otherwise, White pushes the pawn all the way to b5, b6 etc., and Black can't transfer the rook to the b-file via the 7th or 2nd rank.  56.dxe6  Rxe6  57.b5  Re2+  58.Kf1  Rb2  59.Rd8  Rxb5  60.Rxd6  Kf5=  Black should be able to make a draw due its active king, rook, and a passed pawn. }
55. b4 f3+ 56. Rxf3 Rxd4 57. Re3
{ Briefly misses a win. Black blunders 2 moves later, bringing White back to the winning game.  57.Rb3  The usual move - put the rook behind the passed pawn and win.  57...Rxd5  58.b5  Kxh6  59.b6  Rg5+  60.Kf3  Rg8  61.b7  Rb8  62.Ke4  e6  63.Rb5  Kg6  64.Kd4  Kf7  65.h4+-  The winning plan here is to move the king around Black's pawns all the way to a7. }
57... Rxd5 58. Rxe7 Kxh6 59. Kf3 Rd4
{ The final blunder, missing a draw.  59...Kg6  60.Ke3  Kf6  The king needs to arrive to e6 and move towards the b-pawn.  61.Rh7  Rb5  62.Rh4  Ke6= }
60. Re4 { The rest is simple. White wins the endgame without any trouble. }
60... Rd3+ 61. Re3 Rd5 62. Rb3 Rb5 63. Ke4 Kg5 64. Kd4 Kf6 65. Kc4 Rb6 66. Kd5
Ke7 67. b5 Kd7 68. h4 Kc7 69. h5 Rb8 70. h6 Rh8 71. Rh3 Rh7 72. b6+ Kxb6 73.
