1. d4
{ 1.Nf3  Through a different move order, we arrive to the same position in our course after move 11.  1...Nf6  2.b3  g6  3.Bb2  Bg7  4.g3  O-O  5.Bg2  d6  6.d4  c5  7.c4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  d5  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.O-O  Nb4  11.Na3 }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 c5 7. c4 cxd4 8. Nxd4
d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bb2 Nb4 11. Na3
{ This position will occur in one of the lines in Chapter 1. } 11... N8c6 12.
Nxc6 Nxc6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bxc6
{ A powerful capture, leading the game into an advantageous endgame for White. Usually, the knight is better than a bishop if the side with the bishop has multiple pawn weaknesses. Here, Black will struggle on the queenside due to weak a7 and c6 pawns. }
14... bxc6 15. Rc1
{ 15.Qc1!  Would have been more precise since the queen attacks the c6 and protects the knight on a3 in case Black goes Qa5. }
15... Qa5
{ Allows White to trade queens comfortably.  15...Bh3  The only move that keeps Black afloat.  16.Re1  a5  The pawn push to a4 is accompanied by a pawn sacrifice on c6 but Black cares more about the initiative than the pawn.  17.Rxc6  a4  18.b4  Rc8⩲  Black's counterplay is surprisingly sticky here. The queenside is open, the pawn on b4 is not safe, the bishop can retreat to e6 and hit the pawn on a2 - all these factors favor the bishop. }
16. Qd4+ Kg8 17. Qb2
{ 17.Qc5!  White missed a chance to trade the queens instantly and proceed to a risk-free endgame, where Black will face a painful defense of the queenside pawns. }
17... Bh3 18. Rfd1 Rad8 19. Nc4 Qh5
{ We would call this a decisive mistake. Black doesn't get a chance to avoid the queen trade comfortably anymore.  19...Rxd1+  20.Rxd1  Rd8!  The saving move, taking advantage of the White's weak back rank.  21.Rxd8+  Qxd8  22.Qd2⩲  White is still better but at least Black can preserve the queens for the future counterplay. }
20. Qe5 { The queen on e5 is gorgeous, controlling the entire board. } 20...
Qh6 21. Ne3 Be6 22. h4 Rc8
{ 22...Rxd1+  Sometimes, the game is so bad that the only chance to save it is to go to an endgame, and hope it's going to be a draw because of the lack of material.  23.Rxd1  Qg7  The queen on h6 was so bad that keeping it there would only make Black's game worse.  24.Qa5±  White still dominates the game. If Black tries to stir the pot after Qb2, we can calmly respond with Kf1 and even move the king to e1 if they check us on h3 with bishop. }
23. Rc5
{ From now on, White's advantage is undeniable. White did a good job converting it into a win. }
23... Qg7 24. Qxg7+ Kxg7 25. Rdc1 Bd7 26. Ra5 Ra8 27. Nc4
{ The knight will travel to e5 and then to c5 via d3, blocking the c6 pawn and making ensuring it stays a weakness permanently. }
27... Rfc8 28. Ne5 Be8 29. Rac5 Rc7 30. b4 Rac8 31. Ra5 f6 32. Nd3 Bf7 33. Nc5
f5 34. Rd1 Bd5 35. f3
{ Potentially, preparing e4 and hitting the bishop on d5. } 35... Kf6 36. Kf2
h6 37. Ra6 Kf7 38. a3
{ White is not in a rush since Black is pretty much in a zugzwang, lacking any meaningful moves. }
38... g5 39. h5
{ The pawn on h5 could be useful later in case we pick up on h6. As a general rule, don't trade too many pawns if you are trying to win. }
39... Bc4 40. Ra5 Rb8
{ A blunder in a lost position. However, White doesn't immediately pick up on it. }
41. Rd7
{ 41.Rd4  Ends Black's suffering super quickly.  41...Bd5  42.Na6+-   41...Bb5  42.a4+- }
41... Rbc8 42. Rxa7 Rxd7 43. Nxd7
{ The remaining moves were not strictly necessary as this position warrants a resignation on a Grand Master level. }
43... Be6 44. Nc5 Bc4 45. Nd7 Be6 46. Ne5+ Kf6 47. Nd3 Bc4 48. Ra5 Rd8 49. Ke3
Bb5 50. a4 { White goes into a winning rook endgame. } 50... Bxd3 51. exd3 Rb8
52. b5 cxb5 53. Rxb5 Rc8 54. Rb6+ e6 55. Rb1
{ Complicates the game a little bit.  55.Rb5  We could also win by protecting the pawn sideways.  55...Ra8  56.a5  Ra6  57.d4+- }
55... Ra8 56. Ra1 Ra5
{ 56...f4+  Black missed a chance to prolong the game a bit.  57.gxf4  gxf4+  58.Kxf4  Ra5  59.Ke4  Kf7  60.f4  Ke7  61.d4  Kd6  62.Kd3  White needs to realize that the only winning plan is to drop the pawn on h5 and move the king to b4, thus finally being able to push the pawn to a5.  62...Kc6  63.Kc4+- }
57. Kd4
{ The rest now is easy. White just needs to bring the king to b4 and then push the a-pawn. }
57... g4 58. f4 e5+ 59. fxe5+ Ke6 60. Ra2 Rd5+ 61. Kc4 Kxe5 62. a5 Rd4+ 63. Kc3
Rd7 64. a6 Ra7 65. Ra5+ Kf6 66. Kd2 Kg5 67. d4 Kxh5 68. Rxf5+ Kg6 69. Ra5 h5
70. Ke3 Re7+ 71. Kf2 Rf7+ 72. Ke2 Ra7 73. Kd3 Kh6 74. Ke4 Re7+ 75. Kf4 Rf7+ 76.
